<HEAD>Former Sect Pastor Gets 2-Year Prison Term In Boy's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge on Monday sentenced the former pastor of a faith-healing sect to two years in prison for his part in the death of the son of church members, saying he wanted to send a message to cultists. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was convicted of second-degree criminal mistreatment. <ORGANIZATION> Spokane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> said circumstances warranted going beyond the standard 90-day sentence for the crime, the maximum the prosecutor sought. `` I have an obligation to send a message ... to anyone who might be interested in beginning a religious cult,'' <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> told <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> was the former pastor of a nameless Christian sect that eschewed conventional medicine in favor of prayer. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, the 10-year-old son of sect members <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> and <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, died Dec. 20, 1987, of untreated juvenile diabetes. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, 43, was convicted last month of first-degree manslaughter for failing to seek medical attention for his son. Charges against Mrs. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> were dismissed prior to the trial. `` Why is it that it takes a tragedy for people to realize what they've been doing is wrong?'' asked <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON>. `` Medicine has been given to us by <PERSON> God </PERSON> as much as the power of prayer.'' <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> also was sentenced to serve six months for a charge of simple assault stemming from a spanking administered to an adult church member in a separate incident. That sentence will be served concurrently, meaning <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> will be eligible for parole in 16 months, <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> said. Before he was sentenced, a tearful <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> told <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> he was `` absolutely ashamed'' of his participation in the sect and its `` rigid view of the outside world.'' `` I am absolutely heartbroken for what happened to <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> said. Testimony during the three-week trial indicated the gravely ill boy was beaten the day before his death by his father and sect founder <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON> while <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> and other church elders watched. The beatings were believed necessary to get the boy to confess the sin of masturbation and be healed. As pastor, <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> knew, or should have known, that <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> was vulnerable, <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> said. Spankings and other discipline of the 10-year-old `` manifested deliberate cruelty,'' the judge said. <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Champaign-Urbana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, has pleaded guilty to second-degree criminal mistreatment and is scheduled to be sentenced later. Testimony also revealed that members were expected to consult with church leaders on matters ranging from buying a car to their sex lives. The fellowship once claimed 300 adult members in four states, but disbanded in February.
