<HEAD>Khmer Bust Auction Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A five-headed Khmer bust of <PERSON> Siva </PERSON>, the Hindu god of destruction and reproduction, has sold for $ 574,200, an auction record for any Southeast Asian work of art at auction, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s said The 31 -LCB- - inch high, gray sandstone bust was sold Monday by an anonynmous collector and bought by an unidentified overseas bidder The figure dated from the third quarter of the 10th century. No history of it was otherwise recorded, except that the uppermost head had been in the Pan Asian Collection, most of which is in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>. Each of the heads wears an enigmatic smile. The uppermost head was acquired by the seller, who reunited it with the rest of the figure. The sale at Monday's auction of some 100 lots of Khmer, Thai, Indian and Himalayan art totaled $ 2.8 million. The three top-priced lots were sold by the same collector. A 7th century head of <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, larger than lifesize, was bought for $ 376,200 by a Swiss collector. Another anonymous buyer paid a similar price for a 4-foot standing figure of a Khmer four-armed male deity from the first half of the 9th century. The bidders included <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Swiss collectors and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealers.
