<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Weigh Rejection of Draft Vatican Document</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT FURLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> is moving toward a showdown vote on whether to reject a draft <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> document questioning the theological authority of such conferences. The bishops softened the wording of their proposed reply to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> document on Monday but pressed toward a scheduled Wednesday vote without changing their underlying judgment: `` The draft is not suitable.'' Despite frequent public compliments from both sides, relations have often been uneasy between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and bishops' conferences, particularly those such as the Americans' which have seemed to be growing in prestige in recent years. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II has publicly supported many of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conference's efforts, including national pastoral letters that stirred controversy outside the church for their criticism of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policies on nuclear arms and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. However, there also has been criticism from high <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials, who have asked for whom the bishops were speaking in commenting on matters of doctrine, and on what authority. Also on Monday, acceding to a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> request, the bishops postponed a vote on another controversial item _ but did so only grudgingly and with rare public complaints about the way church leaders in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> had handled the situation. While the bishops gave ground, they took pains to say they were not knuckling under to <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> pressure. `` We have not bowed obsequiously to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in an untoward fashion,'' said Archbishop <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipscomb </PERSON> of Mobile, <LOC