om the proposed rejection notice. The new version, distributed by a committee of past conference presidents on Monday, is considerably toned down from the original, which had used such phrases as `` rigid and confusing'' and `` overly defensive and negative'' to describe the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> draft. However, it still calls for the bishops to label the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> effort `` non-placet,'' so flawed that it is n't even suitable to be used as a basis for revision. Several bishops objected to such a label, suggesting it would be a slap at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. This raised the possibility that the conference's objections would have to be softened further if they are to win the two-thirds majority necessary in Wednesday's vote. In other action Monday, the bishops: _ Gave first reading to one proposal that would call for easing of a 1986 law and give legal standing to many more undocumented Hispanic workers, and to another resolution calling for acceleration of religious freedom and an end to intimidation of worshipers in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other Eastern bloc countries _ Postponed action on a resolution calling for movement toward normalization of relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> Archbishop <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Vietnamese-American </PERSON> groups in this country were divided on the issue, but he said the postponement was merely to give the bishops time to consider conditions in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> in general. _ Heard Archbishop <PERSON> Pio </PERSON> <PERSON> Laghi </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> representative to the bishops as well as to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, call for greater effort in keeping Hispanic-Americans in the church He did not publicly mention the simmering Vatican-bishops disputes.
