<HEAD>Trade Problems To Face Incoming Agriculture Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nagging trade problems and preliminary maneuvering on a new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm bill will face the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's incoming secretary of agriculture next year. Lobbying for the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post already is in full swing, although President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his advisors have been focusing on other matters and have dropped no hints about who might get the job. Trade issues will be near the top of the agenda for the new agriculture secretary. Little progress has been made in reaching agreement on farm provisions of a new 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- agreement, despite two years of talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> call for phasing out farm subsidies by the year 2000 has received a chilly reception. Also stalled are talks aimed at reaching a new long-term grain agreement with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The most recent, five-year agreement expired Sept. 30 and there have been no formal talks since Oct. 24, when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rejected a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> proposal calling for a one-year agreement. A free-trade agreement that would phase out most tariffs between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> had been approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but is running into trouble in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. That is not viewed as altogether bad among some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat producers and potato growers who never had much use for the pact anyway. Failure of the agreement, however, would be guaranteed to make life more complex for the next agriculture secretary. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committees </ORGANIZATION> plan to start talking next year about a farm bill to replace the omnibus 1985 farm legislation that expires in two years. The 1985 law is largely a blueprint for a massive cleanout of huge grain surpluses that had piled up, driving down prices and bringing on what came to be known as the crisis in rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Huge subsidies were provided to boost exports at clearance sale prices as part of the effort to make farm surpluses disappear. Surplus milk and cheese remaining on the shelf were simply given away to the poor. The measure is generally viewed as a success. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts say net cash income for the farm sector in 1988 should be near, and may top by a small margin last year's record $ 57.1 billion, despite the summer drought. For that reason many in the agricultural community think there will be little change in the thrust of the next bill. But the secretary is certain to face an array of tough challenges as lawmakers set about their work. New programs to help specific crops are bound to be debated along with plans to reform the troubled federal crop insurance program and further tighten pesticide regulation. With the 70-year-old Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> saying the time for retirement has arrived, or at least will when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is sworn in, candidates are lining up for the secretary's job. One who says he does not want to serve in the Cabinet and would like to return to private industry is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. The one-time <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> feedlot operator had long been mentioned as a possible future agriculture secretary. Getting a strong boost from congressional Republicans is Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, R-Mo. He is a force on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> but is not a farmer and, thus, like <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>, might need to have someone with experience in production agriculture in the deputy secretary's slot <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s deputy, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, raised crops and livestock in southeastern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> between 1955 and 1982, when he came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to become head of the Soil and <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. He has become a favorite at <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign assurances to voters that he is an environmentalist might sway him to opt for <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, the architect of several major soil conservation measures contained in the 1985 farm law. That far from exhausts the list. If <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s low-key, businesslike approach captures <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s fancy, the new president could turn to <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lesher </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consultant and former <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> business partner. Also being mentioned are former Rep. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> soybean farmer <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> past President <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Delano </PERSON>.
