<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, at least for now, is keeping out of the continuing national debate over abortion rights. The justices on Monday refused to give husbands legal power to prevent their wives from terminating pregnancies. Without comment, they rejected arguments by an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> man who said he had `` fundamental rights and interests in his unborn child.'' The action left intact a state court ruling that upheld a mother's right to have an abortion. There has been speculation that an increasingly conservative high court is prepared to take a new look at its landmark 1973 ruling, <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, that legalized abortion nationwide. The author of the 12-year-old court opinion, Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, has said he believes there is `` a very distinct possibility'' <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> will be reversed during the court's current term But on Monday, the justices gave no signs they are eager to tackle an abortion controversy now. The court let stand a ruling last July by the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that said allowing a husband to block a wife's abortion is barred by past high court rulings. The high court in 1976 struck down a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law requiring spousal consent before a woman could obtain an abortion during the first 12 weeks of her pregnancy. The <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> case stems from an attempt last summer by <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Conn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Elkhart </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, to prevent his estranged wife, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>, from having an abortion. She was about six weeks pregnant at the time. A state trial judge issued a temporary order barring Mrs. <PERSON> Conn <