<HEAD>President-elect Covets Time For Exercise, Fishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, just finished with a two-mile run, bounded across the beach and threw himself into the choppy waters. He caught a wave, body-surfed in and swam around a while. Later he waded back in shoulder-deep to cast a fishing line against the brisk waves. After an hour or so, he took a break to visit his mother and go to church, then piloted a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs power boat some 40 miles back down the coast and leaped into the water for more fishing. Afterward he played nine holes of golf. This was a typical vacation day for the 64-year-old man who takes over the White House next Jan. 20. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> showed during his four-day stay in this balmy beach community that his idea of relaxation is physical activity. He enjoys a variety of outdoor sports. One day he followed his morning jog with a trip out to a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter 400 yards offshore in a motorized raft. He jumped off the cutter and swam part of the way in, then grabbed a rope off the raft for an arm-numbing tow to shore against the choppy waters. White House physician Dr. <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> has pronounced <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s fitness `` exceptional for a man his age'' and expressed amazement at his health and stamina His loping walk is that of a younger man, and he moves around a tennis court with an alacrity that makes up for his unimpressive serve. In an Election Day match, he and son <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> played doubles with son <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and son-in-law <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBlond </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, just hours before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> learned he had been elected president. The president-to-be lunged for balls and zigzagged across the court, energetic and clearly competitive with the younger men. Toward the end of his long presidential campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> complained of physical fatigue, saying he missed having the time to jog, which he said invigorates him. Often on the campaign trail he had a stationary bicycle brought to his hotel room. Since the election, he seems to be making up for the inactivity of long airplane rides and motorcades. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told reporters in a beachfront news conference that his Friday-through-Tuesday morning vacation in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> helped him clear his mind. `` I've been able to run every day,'' he said. `` I love the fishing. It does n't matter what you catch, it's the fact you're out there and fishermen know that. And so I'm still of the <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> school, that the days I spend fishing should not be deducted from the time I spend on earth.''
