<HEAD>Nobel Laureate Steps Up Criticism Of Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the Nobel laureate and Soviet human rights activist, says Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is using `` undemocratic means'' in attempts to improve conditions in their country. `` From my point of view this is dangerous,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said. He spoke Monday to a group of American intellectuals after comparing notes on human rights and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House. Today, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> is scheduled to receive the <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> peace prize and a $ 50,000 award for making `` an enormous impact on the conscience of the world.'' A nuclear physicist who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> has long been the principal human rights advocate in his country. He was confined to virtual house arrest in Gorky for six years until <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> arranged his release in 1986. The Soviet leader also arranged for <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s first visit to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, at a session Monday of the <ORGANIZATION> Woodrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scholars </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may not have a long-range program for reform. He said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> improvises, and often `` compromises with existing forces that negate his efforts.'' Specifically, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear physicist criticized <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s consolidation of power, the absence of multi-party and free-market systems as well as restrictions on meetings and demonstrations `` There is no clear realization how this system should be reformed,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said. In fact, he said, the partial reforms arranged by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> could lead to `` disequilibrium.'' Before leaving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on his first trip to the West, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> leveled similar criticisms at the Soviet president. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> supports glasnost _ a term for openness that has marked <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s 3 -LCB- years in power _ but complains that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader has accumulated too much power as both president and Communist party chief. `` His tactic seems to be getting democratic reforms through undemocratic means,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said. `` From my point of view this is a dangerous action.'' On the human rights front, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said some dissidents remain in psychiatric institutions along with many more people who were chronic critics of their employers. He called the detention system `` one of the most acute abuses'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Earlier, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> discussed the plight of dissidents with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House. The president said until the problem is `` completely eliminated'' human rights will remain an irritant in U.S.-Soviet relations. The 67-year-old <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for about 20 minutes in the Oval Office. They shared a cautious approach to the measures taken by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, mindful of reporters at a picture-taking session, drew <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s attention to two dissidents, <PERSON> Vazif </PERSON> <PERSON> Meylanov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Kukobaka </PERSON>, who <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said still are being held. He called the detention of <PERSON> Meylanov </PERSON> `` ironic'' since he was sent to prison protesting the removal of <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to Gorky in 1980. `` I'm free to travel and he is in prison,'' the human rights activist said. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, speaking through an interpreter, said <PERSON> Kukobaka </PERSON> is in prison for refusing to bear false witness against a foreign diplomat. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as more cooperative than any <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader before him, but said `` we can only wait and see'' if the Soviet leader makes good on a promise to release all political prisoners. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> told the president `` there are only individuals'' left in jails, implying that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in principle at least, does not adhere to a policy of detaining dissidents for their views. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, also voiced concern about the impact that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s missile defense program, known popularly as Star Wars, might have on efforts by the superpowers to negotiate a cut in long-range nuclear missile stockpiles.
