<HEAD>Energy Department Corrects Natural Gas Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department says it overestimated how much natural gas American industry has been using, a mistake that had set off false alarms about the energy efficiency of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. The error arose when a new reporting form confused many of the companies that report gas deliveries to the department's <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> EIA </ORGANIZATION>'s quarterly publication `` Short Term Energy Outlook'' for October, which reached users Monday, said the previous quarter's estimates of industrial natural gas consumption in the first half of 1988 were about 8 percent too high The agency started checking its statistics when the July edition of its outlook reported a 26 percent first-half increase in industrial gas use, implausibly high. In fact, the first half increase was about 6 percent to 3.13 trillion cubic feet. Natural gas is a major source of energy for home heating, electricity generation, chemical manufacture and industrial process heat. A little less than a quarter of all energy comes frm gas; industrial gas use is about 8 percent of the total national energy bill. Without the exaggerated natural gas changes, there would have been no significant change in the estimated energy efficiency in the economy, the closely watched ratio of energy used in producing a dollar's worth of goods and services. Environmentalists use this as a rough indicator of damage to the environment from economic activity; policymakers watch it as an indication of future vulnerability to interruption of oil imports. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EIA </ORGANIZATION> analyst, said the agency distributed new reporting forms to gas companies delivering gas to industrial users with the start of 1988. The new forms asked for physical deliveries of gas no matter who owned it. The old forms required listing deliveries only of gas owned by the reporting company, no matter who delivered it. Some companies continued to report the old way, which meant some gas was counted twice _ once by the owner, once by the shipper. <ORGANIZATION> EIA </ORGANIZATION> said `` 43 companies apparently have consistently misreported their monthly'' deliveries, resulting in `` an overstatement of industrial consumption in the first six months of 1988 of 0.5 trillion cubic feet.'' Now that the errors have been corrected, the agency expects industrial gas use of 6.15 trillion cubic feet for all of 1988, only a 4.4 percent gain, instead of the 19 percent increase projected in July on the basis of the overestimates. The energy crises of the 1970s prompted major efficiency improvements everywhere. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, for example, autos averaged about 13 miles per gallon of gasoline in 1973; <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> required 27.5 mpg by 1985, a goal since relaxed to 26 mpg. More efficient processes have continued to be introduced in industry, and energy efficiency gains accelerated from an average of 1.2 percent per year in the 1970s to 2.8 percent in 1980-1986. But in 1987, for the first time in 11 years, efficiency failed to improve, a stagnation many analysts attributed to the collapse in oil prices of 1986. It took 19,960 British thermal units, or Btu, to produce a dollar's worth of goods and services in 1987, measured in dollars of 1982 buying power. This was roughly the same as the 19,950 Btu of 1986. A Btu is a standard unit of energy, equal to the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit. In July the agency forecast a 1988 ratio of 20,180 Btu per dollar, or a 1.1 percent decline from 1987, and a 1989 ratio of 20,050, a 0.6 percent improvement from 1988. The corrected October forecast predicts 19,840 Btu per dollar, an improvement of 0.6 percent from 1987, and improvement of 1.3 percent to 19,590 Btu in 1989. One analyst, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Durning </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Worldwatch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an environmental research group, said, `` I could believe'' an improvement of 0.6 percent. `` I would expect gains ... in the aggregate of about a half percent per year, just from the technologies and how much room for improvement there is, almost indefinitely,'' <PERSON> Durning </PERSON> said. But at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Berkeley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, analyst <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Schipper </PERSON> said that even after the data corrections, `` As far as I'm concerned that's no change. There's a plateau. ... If I were a policymaker I'd be worried.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
