<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet space shuttle Buran touched down on a concrete runway in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> on Tuesday morning, flawlessly ending its unmanned 3 hour, 25 minute maiden voyage, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> has successfuly tested its first reusable space craft Buran,'' the official radio said. `` The unmanned shuttle has just landed on a special runway near the Baikonur Space Center,'' it said, interrupting its regular programming. The delta-winged Buran, Russian for snowstorm, had orbited Earth twice, lifting off on schedule despite a cold rain. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the shuttle landed exactly on schedule. A previous attempt to launch the Buran had been frustrated by last-minute technical troubles. The shuttle was launched at 6 a.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 10 p.m. Monday EST -RRB- in yellow flame and clouds of white steam from the special launch site in the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. Forty-seven minutes later it reached orbit, firing its own rockets for the first time. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle lookalike completed two orbits and then returned to the 2.7-mile concrete landing strip eight miles from its launch pad. Before liftoff, technicians had been concerned that the Buran and <ORGANIZATION> Energia </ORGANIZATION> might get covered with a coat of ice.
