<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Shuttle Lands After Brief, Flawless Unmanned Maiden Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with details of landing, quotes. Picks up
graf 9 pvs, `The craft's ...' INCORPORATES a0448, AM-Shuttle Lands.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet space shuttle Buran touched down Tuesday morning on a concrete runway in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, flawlessly ending its unmanned 3-hour, 25-minute maiden flight, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said. Buran had flown twice around <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> on fully automatic control, then landed at the special 2.7-mile concrete runway eight miles from its launch pad at the Baikonur Cosmodrome. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> has successfuly tested its first reusable space craft Buran,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said, interrupting its regular programming. A previous attempt to launch the Buran had been frustrated by last-minute technical troubles. An escort plane followed the shuttle as it approached the runway, tracking the last moments of the flight with special optical and television equipment. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the shuttle systems of the Buran, or snowstorm in Russian, were tested during the completely automated flight. In yellow flame and clouds of steam, the delta-winged Buran lifted off on schedule at 6 a.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time -LRB- 10 p.m. EST -RRB- despite a cold rain, indicating there had been no hitches in the automated countdown and launch. The engines of Buran were fired twice about three-quarters of an hour later after it had separated from its booster Energia, and the craft reached orbit exactly on schedule, Soviet media said. There was no live broadcast of the liftoff, but 90 minutes later Soviet television showed its first film. The shuttle, attached to <LOCATION> Energia </LOCATION> and four first-stage rockets, lifted slowly off its pad in the early morning dark. Controllers were shown applauding the launch and green computer screens showed the flight trajectory. The craft's own engines were fired for the first time at an altitude of 99 miles to nudge it into orbit with its left wing facing <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Before liftoff, technicians had been concerned that the Buran and <ORGANIZATION> Energia </ORGANIZATION> might get covered with a coat of ice. `` If the wind rises into a squall and the orbital vehicle -LRB- and -RRB- <LOCATION> Energia </LOCATION> become covered with a crust of ice, then launch time will be changed again,'' said correspondent <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Slipchenko </PERSON>, referring to a failed attempt to launch Buran last month. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials wo n't launch the American space shuttle if there is ice on the booster rocket or orbiter, and cold temperatures contributed to the failure of booster rocket seals that led to the Challenger disaster in January 1986. The radio report said the flight would be long enough to check out all the shuttle systems and determine when a manned flight is feasible. Technicians began fueling the 198-foot <ORGANIZATION> Energia </ORGANIZATION>, the world's most powerful booster, with nearly 2,000 tons of liquid hydrogen, oxygen and kerosene, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday night. Launch had been set for Oct. 29, but the countdown was halted with 51 seconds left when an access arm failed to pull far enough away from the space craft. Officials said Monday they redesigned the joint and expected no more trouble from it. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> flew its first shuttle, the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, in 1981, and for years the Soviets criticized the craft as wasteful and unreliable. But Western space specialists say the Soviets began planning their space plane in 1982 at the latest. Few technical details have been made public about the Buran, a lookalike to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle, and state-run media have only indirectly indicated its cost. `` Comparing the cost of the Buran program and that of the similar <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle program -LRB- $ 10 billion -RRB-, newspapers say they are approximately identical,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The Buran can carry up to 10 cosmonauts, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaev </PERSON>, chief of the commercial Soviet space agency Glavkosmos, told reporters Thursday the maiden flight of the 100-ton Buran will show the Soviets if they are ready to begin manned shuttle missions. The Soviets have cited the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the Challenger, which killed all seven crewmembers aboard, as an example of the hazards they are trying to avoid. <PERSON> Dunaev </PERSON> said the Buran and `` several'' additional shuttles planned by the Soviets will have a different role than their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> equivalents, which were designed to ferry payloads into orbit. The Buran and its sister craft will be used to park satellites in space `` only in exceptional cases,'' <PERSON> Dunaev </PERSON> said, since the use of shuttles for that purpose costs `` tens, even hundreds of times'' more than conventional booster rockets. `` Soviet reusable spaceships will be used, first of all, for the accomplishment of tasks involved in the operation of space technology: maintenance operations and recovery of worn-out satellites,'' he said. The Soviets repeatedly have criticized the military uses of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle, but the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> says the Soviet spacecraft could be used to deploy killer satellites, ballistic missile defense weapons and other military uses. The Energia, which can lift a 220,000-pound payload, rivals the power of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s huge <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> 5 rocket, which was scrapped for economy reasons after taking Apollo crews to the moon.
</TEXT>
