<HEAD>Congressman Denies He Was Part Of Alleged Cover-Up After Shuttle
Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> says he was thinking of the Challenger astronauts' families, not about any cover-up concerning the shuttle explosion, when he intervened in a dispute over the astronauts' remains. `` It's the last thing in the wake of an American tragedy -LRB- that -RRB- there should be a bureaucratic turf fight over who's going to possess the remains of the seven dead astronauts,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said Monday. `` That simply was not right in the context of the national tragedy we were all suffering, and it was not right for the families of the seven astronauts. `` If I had to do it all over again, I would do it exactly the same way,'' he said at a news conference. A story published Sunday in The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tropic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrat who chairs the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, acted at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s behest in calling <LOCATION> Brevard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Medical Examiner <PERSON> Laudie </PERSON> <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> and telling him to drop his office's contention that the autopsies should be performed by <LOCATION> Brevard </LOCATION> authorities The article implied <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s actions were part of an alleged <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> cover-up aimed at preventing the public from knowing that the astronauts likely were alive until the Challenger slammed into the ocean on Jan. 28, 1986. Autopsy reports from the county office would have been public record. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> denied the story's report that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbey </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Astronaut Office, called him to ask him to intervene in the autopsy dispute. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said he called Abbey in March 1986 to tell him he thought the dispute was inappropriate and that he would call the <LOCATION> Brevard </LOCATION> medical examiner. In <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> on Monday, the wives of Challenger astronauts <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> <PERSON> Onizuka </PERSON> said they were n't surprised to read speculation that crew members may have been alive during the 2 -LCB- - minute free fall into the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, but that the Tropic article was distressing `` I think I always felt that <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> was alive because his <ORGANIZATION> PEAP </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- personal emergency air pack -RRB- was found still attached to his seat ... breathed down three-fourths of the way, which was the same amount of time that it would've taken to impact,'' <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` It was in the on position and it is used only on demand, so he had to be breathing in order to receive the air. I have known in my heart always, I felt strongly that he was alive until that time.'' Added <PERSON> Lorna </PERSON> <PERSON> Onizuka </PERSON>: `` I do n't know if anything was covered up, I hope not. It was an incident that nobody was prepared for ... or how to handle it when it did happen.'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, an astronaut aboard the last shuttle mission before Challenger, said the astronauts' remains had been recovered in international waters and taken to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pathology </ORGANIZATION>, and as far as he was concerned a presidential executive order signed in February gave the independent <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> the jurisdiction for all aspects of the Challenger investigation. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> agreed with him, attributing the dispute to an assistant medical examiner. <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>'s office said he was unavailable for comment Monday. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials denied they were trying to cover up details of the astronauts' deaths. `` We've made every effort to determine the cause and time of death but have never been able to pin it down,'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Atchison </PERSON> said Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said that if there were lingering doubts about the Challenger disaster, his subcommittee would hold new hearings. But, he said, the possibility that the astronauts were alive until impact was n't new.
