<HEAD>More Jobs Opened to Women in Military Following Discrimination
Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is opening 11,138 jobs to women after a year-long review of the military's treatment of its female personnel. `` I think the overall message is that the secretary -LRB- of defense -RRB- is firmly committed to opening all positions to women that are compatible with existing laws and statutes,'' said Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armor </PERSON>, the principal deputy assistant secretary for manpower. The decision announced Monday, when combined with previous moves by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, brings to more than 24,000 the number of once closed positions opened to women since the review began in October 1987. Women comprise 10.4 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces, or about 217,400 enlisted personnel and officers of the 2.1 million total.
