<HEAD>Educational Testing Organizations Adopt Code of Fair Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six educational testing organizations have agreed to a voluntary code that commits them to strive for fairness in tests given students of different races, sex or ethnic backgrounds. The Code of Fair Testing Practices in Education announced Monday was endorsed by six companies whose tests are taken by millions of American students each year, from first grade to graduate school. The voluntary code also commits the test makers to review and revise questions `` to avoid potentially insensitive content or language,'' and to offer `` appropriately modified forms of tests'' to the handicapped. The signers of the new code are: <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CTB </ORGANIZATION> @ <PERSON> McGraw </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Psychological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Riverside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
