<FIRST>r i PM-Buran-History 1stLd-Wriththru   11-15 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buran-History, 1st Ld-Wriththru,a0470,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Space Plane Looks Familiar, But Uses May Vary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to RECAST, ADD byline. Picks up graf 3
pvs, `In appearance ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet officials, who once criticized the American space shuttle as wasteful and unreliable, joined the shuttle business today with a craft that looks conspiciously like its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> predecessor. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency even acknowledged similarities between the crafts after its space plane, the Buran, made its maiden unmanned flight today. `` In appearance the Buran resembles the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space shuttle, which has the same streamlined forms and double-delta wing _ the laws of aerodynamics are international,'' it said. Despite the similarity in appearance and design, however, the Soviets seem to have settled on different uses for their shuttle, named the Buran, which is Russian for snowstorm. For years, the Soviets would n't even admit they were developing their own shuttle, though Western specialists date the program back to at least 1982. In June 1980, 10 months before the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> launched its first shuttle, the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the chief of Soviet cosmonaut training, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatalov </PERSON>, said Soviet officials `` consider that the employment of these spacecraft is not justified for Soviet research because present tasks can be solved with the well-tested methods in an economical way.'' Former cosmonaut <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feoktistov </PERSON>, writing in 1984 in a Soviet newspaper, praised the American shuttle as `` an impressive engineering achievement.'' But, he added, `` this system is not sound economically and technologically.'' Soviet officials appeared to become believers after settling on a different focus for their shuttle than the one <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> chose. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle was designed primarily to ferry satellites into orbit. But <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunayev </PERSON>, the head of the Soviet space agency Glavkosmos, said in 1987 that shuttles are not as economical as single-use rocket boosters for placing satellites into orbit. In the clearest hint of the Soviet shuttle's purpose, he said such craft are valuable for servicing space stations and satellites and recovering objects from orbit. The reasoning seems sound because ever since they pioneered space flight with the 1957 launch of Sputnik, the Soviets have forged a proven track record for launching satellites on single-use rockets. They put up more than 150 satellites a year, more than any other country. In addition, the Soviets have concentrated on maintaining a permanent manned presence in space aboard the orbiting space station Mir. While Soviet officials have not said whether the shuttle is capable of doing so, the shuttle might be able to ferry supplies and cosmonauts to Mir. The Buran might also have the capability to retrieve and repair potentially dangerous satellites in orbit. The Soviets have repeatedly criticized the military use of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> shuttle, and the next American flight, of the Atlantis in late November, is a mission for the Pentagon. But as with the American shuttle, the Soviets might use the Buran for military missions. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says the Soviet shuttle could be used to deploy anti-satellite and ballistic missile defense weapons. It is n't clear whether the Soviets will try to market their shuttle's services to foreign customers, as they have done with their <ORGANIZATION> Proton </ORGANIZATION> rocket boosters. If foreign customers are sought, competition will come not only from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> hopes to have its version of the shuttle, the <ORGANIZATION> Hermes </ORGANIZATION>, on the launch pad in the late 1990s. The Buran clearly has advantages over its <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cousin. Its separate booster rocket, the <ORGANIZATION> Energia </ORGANIZATION>, is powered only by liquid fuels, which can be extinguished in an emergency. It has no solid-fuel boosters like the one that failed on the Challenger, killing seven crewmembers. In addition, the Soviet shuttle can use jet engines in its tail, giving it more maneuverability in landing than its American counterpart. The Buran can also carry far heavier payloads than the American shuttle. Energia can hoist more than 100 tons, and the orbiter itself can carry about 66,000 pounds. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shuttle can carry about 55,000 pounds. While Soviet officials maintain they did not copy the American shuttle, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has a different view. `` By using <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> propulsion, computer, materials and airframe technology and design, the Soviets were able to produce an orbiter years earlier, and at far less cost, than if they had depended solely on their own technology and engineering,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in its 1988 report Soviet Military Power.
</TEXT>
