<FIRST>r a PM-ArtAuction     11-15 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art Auction,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Picasso Painting Brings Record Price For 20th Century Art</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private Latin American collector paid nearly $ 25 million at auction for an early <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON> painting of a mother kissing her son's upturned face, setting a record for a 20th century work of art. `` Maternity,'' from the artist's blue period, sold Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Christie </ORGANIZATION>'s for twice its estimate, making it the third-highest price ever paid for a work of art, behind <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' and `` Sunflowers.'' The 1901 oil on canvas was one of 28 post-Impressionist and modern works on sale from the collection of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> motion picture executive, and his wife <PERSON> Edith </PERSON>, the daughter of film mogul, <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>. The 28 lots, all of which sold, fetched $ 85,024,500 _ a record for a single owner's sale at auction. `` This may well be the sale of the century,'' said <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s president <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burge </PERSON>, who presided over the auction `` Tonight's auction was ripe for success _ unsurpassingly beautiful works of art, a fiercely competitive market, and a renowned provenance,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Burge </PERSON> had predicted that the sale would fetch about $ 50 million. The Goetzes built their collection _ generally considered one of the best of its kind _ during the 1940s and 1950s. Until this summer, their paintings hung in their <LOCATION> Holmby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> mansion in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where the couple once entertained lavishly. He died in 1969; she died in June at the age of 82. After intense bidding, `` Maternity'' sold to an unidentified Latin American collector, whose winning bid was placed by telephone. The painting was expected to sell for $ 10 million. It depicts a blue-robed mother in a high-backed chair, with a scissors and sewing basket at her feet. The child, standing next to her, has a ball in his hands. The auction house described the painting as a `` majestic, tender but unsentimental affirmation of maternal love.'' `` It's a great, very rare picture,'' <PERSON> Burge </PERSON> said. `` It was a unique opportunity to buy an early blue period picture'' of <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>'s, who painted it when he was 20, he added. When <PERSON> Burge </PERSON> brought the hammer down on the $ 24.75 million bid, the crowd broke into applause. `` Irises'' sold for $ 53.9 million in November 1987. A few months earlier, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Sunflowers'' sold for $ 39.9 million. The second-highest priced work sold at Monday's auction was <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Monet </PERSON>'s `` The Beach at <LOCATION> Trouville </LOCATION>,'' an 1870 oil on canvas, which went for $ 10.78 million. The third-highest priced piece was <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Degas </PERSON>' `` Little Dancer At 14 Years,'' a statue that sold for $ 10,175,000, a new record for the artist. The statue depicts a dancer in polychromed bronze; she wears a muslin skirt and her hair is tied with a satin ribbon. Eight artist's records were set during the auction; they were for <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, <PERSON> Degas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonnard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Fantin-Latour </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurencin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Soutine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Vuillard </PERSON>. All prices include a 10 percent commission paid by the buyer to the auction house.
</TEXT>
