 A high school teacher will not be disciplined for arranging a field trip in which students were strip-searched, hog-tied and forced to eat fish-head soup in a simulation of Third World prison conditions, officials said. `` Some of the learning activities that were conducted went beyond what was really necessary to accommodate the objectives of the program,'' said <PERSON> Denie </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> Wheaton-Warrenville </LOCATION> school district, at a school board meeting Monday. Superintendent <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON> `` supports the program, the prison simulation,'' she said. `` The administration just feels that parts of it were carried to an extreme.'' Last month's voluntary field trip to <ORGANIZATION> Wheaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> by 34 juniors and seniors from <ORGANIZATION> Wheaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> was intended to give students a taste of criminal-justice systems, included one that might exist in a Third World country ruled by a despot. The field trip included strip-searches, a meal of potato soup with a fish head floating in it, blindfolds, handcuffs and nude `` duck-walking'' involving some of the boys, Ms. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. The students who participated had no complaints, but afterward, some parents said they were outraged by the field trip, and the school board asked <PERSON> Short </PERSON> to evaluate the program. <PERSON> Short </PERSON> told about 50 parents that there would be no disciplinary action against <ORGANIZATION> Wheaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> teacher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliphant </PERSON>, a popular American government instructor who arranged the field trip. But <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said the consent form parents were asked to sign was inadequate. `` We would want to see to it that the communication with parents would be a lot more effective'' in the future, he said. `` There was a need for parents to have a greater understanding of what they were signing.'' The field trip was supervised by <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Smarto </PERSON>, director of the college's <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION>, who acted as the `` warden.'' Two college students were `` guards.''
