<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s rebels has agreed to a cease-fire in his 5 -LCB- - year rebellion and to allow relief to reach starving war refugees, the official <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported today In return, the agency said, renegade army Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> expects a national state of emergency to be lifted and a constitutional conference convened. The agreement was reported in dispatches from the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, where it was to be signed today, and from <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. It does not commit the government, but Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> gave the talks his blessing and said he would follow up on any agreements reached. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> negotiated the agreement with <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirghani </PERSON>, patriarch of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the second partner in <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s governing coalition. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> organized the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in early 1983 and began his fight for southern autonomy and political, economic and administrative reforms. Then-President <PERSON> Gaafar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON>'s proclamation of Islamic law exacerbated the war six months later, and <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> has vowed not to lay down arms until <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s civilian government abrogates <LOCATION> Sharia </LOCATION> Traditionally, the country's Moslem majority dominates the central government. Most of the southerners are Christian or animist. Relief workers say the accumulated effects of more than five years of war have brought widespread famine to much of the south this year. They estimate that 1.3 million of the region's 6 million inhabitants have fled this year alone, with starvation killing more than 250,000 people. There was no immediate reaction to the agreement from the government. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu-Saleh </PERSON> attended the talks as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> leadership. Defense Minister <PERSON> Abdul-Maguid </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Khaleel </PERSON> has said the military would welcome any peace agreement. `` We are the people most concerned about peace, because we suffer more than the others from war,'' <PERSON> Khaleel </PERSON> said. `` We are with the strategy of peace -LRB- but -RRB- will continue defending the territorial integrity of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>.'' The Addis Ababa talks have drawn fire from another coalition partner, the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which saw them as a ploy to force the Moslem party from the government. Any agreement between <PERSON> Mirghani </PERSON> and <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> would make future talks involving the government ineffective, the front's political affairs secretary, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Haj </PERSON>, said. The <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> gave few details on the agreement. The agency said <PERSON> Mirghani </PERSON> described his discussions with <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> as `` serious and frank.''
