<TEXT>
 A warning by Soviet human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> that the West has more to fear from the failure of Kremlin reforms than from their successes goes to the heart of a dilemma facing <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as he prepares to lead American policy. `` The threat of perestroika does n't consist of its success but of its bloody failure. This would be a total calamity,'' said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, conjuring up an image of a newly militant Kremlin again embracing the totalitarianism and expansionism of the Stalin era. With <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s words still ringing, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must ask himself how to deal with Gditions to cooperative ventures. If we do n't, we may one day find ourselves the odd man out, economically and militarily,'' wrote <PERSON> Hough </PERSON>, an outspoken <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> enthusiast. Other analysts believe <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is already in domestic political trouble, that there is little the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can do to help or harm him, and that he is interested in good relations with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as well as with the rest of the West. `` The biggest problem that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> faces now is being blamed by our allies if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> fails,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Oudenaren </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> RAND </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> expert on Soviet relations with the West. While it is true that <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> is out and <PERSON> Dobrynin </PERSON> is down, they are no less hostile to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> than the sometimes acid-tongued <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Falin </PERSON>. Moreover, `` the actual impact that we can have on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is limited,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Oudenaren </PERSON>. `` The biggest challenge is to avoid being blamed for a failure of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.'' Such blame can be avoided by being responsive to his initiatives and having a very active diplomacy toward him.'' `` The chances are that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will fail in some way, or enjoy at most a partial success. The wildest expectations that people in the West have for him are not likely to come to pass,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Oudenaren </PERSON>, echoing a view that is widely held by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and academic experts on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had a hyperactive policy toward <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Oudenaren </PERSON>. And that policy bore fruit in the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, signed last December, and in talks toward a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty. Those negotiations helped convince the presidential electorate that a vote for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was a vote for peace. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may have to keep the same pace if he wishes to make the same argument in 1992.
