fighting to oust the Marxists. Election officers have prepared 33,500 polling stations for Wednesday's vote. Leaders of some 30 political parties contesting the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> polls conferred with their aides after the campaign officially ended midnight Monday. The election promises to be <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s first polls open to political parties in more than a decade. A 25-member international delegation sponsored by the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> will monitor polling unofficially. Troops in armored personnel carriers and sandbagged bunkers watched over the southern cities of <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hyderabad </LOCATION>, scene of a bloodbath in September that killed almost 300 people. Both Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the center-right <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> predicted a sweep of the vote. No reliable public opinion polls were published. At stake Wednesday are seats in the 217-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. On Saturday, voters elect 483 legislators to the four provincial assemblies. Official statistics indicate there are about 48 million eligible voters in this Moslem nation of 107 million people. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ordered voters to present state identity cards at polling stations to prevent fraud. The last open electi