justice's comments; PICKS up 5th graf pvs, ``Canadian euphoria...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> today opened a sweeping general inquiry into the use of illegal drugs in athletics after sprinter <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Johson </PERSON> was stripped of his Olympic gold medal for using steroids. <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> Associate Chief Justice <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubin </PERSON>, appointed by the federal government, said the investigation would examine drug abuse in all Canadian athletics except professional sports. `` This is not an inquiry merely into the conduct of one or more individuals,'' said <PERSON> Dubin </PERSON>, referring to the issue of whether <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> used anabolic steroids, as drug tests showed after his Olympic victory. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> maintains that he never knowingly used drugs to enhance his performances, capped by the world record 9.79 second, 100-meter race at <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, on Sept. 24. <PERSON> Dubin </PERSON> said the inquiry also would examine if too much pressure was being placed on Canadian athletes to encourage them to cheat. `` Are Canadian athletes being exploited by others ... who would risk reputation or health?'' he asked. Canadian euphoria at <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s victory over <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> quickly turned to sadness and disgrace as he was stripped of the medal. `` I would never embarrass my family, my friends, my country and the kids who love me,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said after his return from <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Some remained loyal, and T-shirts appeared with the slogan, `` Ben Did n't Do It.'' They have slipped out of store display windows as the weeks since the Olympics passed. Ironically, the hearings start at a time when Canadians are enmeshed in an unusually passionate debate on their national identity as part of the campaign for next M