<HEAD>Officials Declare War on Stubborn Landfill Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS CAROLA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pungent smoke from an underground landfill fire spread for miles today as firefighters spent a fifth day battling a blaze that is keeping 25 families from their homes. `` This morning, when people got up in <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, they awoke to clouds of steamy, smelly smoke,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> emergency services director. A temperature inversion kept cloud cover low overnight, and smoke from the unlicensed landfill about three miles west of <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> could n't dissipate, Lent said. `` The smell that people complained about does n't mean that it's getting worse It actually means that we're making headway,'' Lent said. Overnight, workers continued their `` wet and smother'' strategy against the blaze, which started Thursday night. Water and air sample results should be available later today, which would determine if the evacuated residents can go home, Lent said. While the dump owner has claimed there was nothing toxic in the landfill, low levels of PCBs were found in the smoke. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials said the level of the chemicals did not exceed federal safety standards. The city of <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> kept in effect a health alert for residents of its west side, and Lent said all residents bothered by the smoke were being advised to stay indoors. Bulldozers and dump trucks dug trenches Monday on two sides of the smoldering area while acrid smoke poured from about two acres of the 17-acre landfill. One trench, 30 feet wide by 30 feet deep and 400 feet long, was filled with dirt Monday to form a firebreak similar to those used in forest fires, Lent said. The other was to be filled in today, he said. It might take days to extinguish the fire, he said. <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> reported 35 people, most of them firefighters, had been treated for respiratory problems from the smoke. No serious injuries have been reported. Lent said the dump contains plastic piping, gypsum board, wood and other building materials placed there by its owner, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rock </PERSON>, who has been charged with operating a dump without a permit.
</TEXT>
