<HEAD>Trial Opens in Sunvalley Mall Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sunvalley is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot of a small plane that crashed into a shopping mall filled with Christmas shoppers and killed seven people covered up serious medical problems, a jury was told. About 70 people are seeking $ 35 million in damages in connection with the Dec. 23, 1985, crash at the <LOCATION> Sunvalley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mall </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>. Opening arguments began Monday. Beech Aircraft, which built the plane in 1962, and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which inspected and maintained it, are defendants in a civil trial to determine whether they should bear any liability for the crash. <ORGANIZATION> Beech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said the crash was caused solely by pilot error when <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, 67, became disoriented in heavy fog. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and his two passengers were among those killed. In addition, more than 70 people were injured. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> lied to doctors who examined him for annual flight physicals in 1983, 1984 and 1985 by saying in answer to a questionnaire item that he had n't seen any doctors during the previous year. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> also stated in 1985 that he was not using any medication when he was taking blood-pressure medicine that can cause drowsiness, <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said. `` There is no way in the world,'' <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> could have passed his 1985 flight physical if he had disclosed his high blood pressure. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> had been taking an amphetamine daily, was receiving injections of testosterone, a steroid, at least twice a month, suffered from a sleeping disorder called early narcolepsy and sometimes fell asleep in his car or at his desk. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON>, an attorney for the plaintiffs, contended that the plane had a defectively designed left engine that performed improperly.
