<HEAD>Legal Affairs Chief Chastises Estonian Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party's chief of legal affairs chastised Estonian leaders for encouraging nationalism and increasing political tension in their tiny republic, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said today. Politburo member <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of the Estonian party had `` committed serious miscalculations in the areas of inter-ethnic relations,'' the official news agency said. <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, whose visit likely was meant as a message to Estonians to tread cautiously, made the remarks in a speech Monday to <LOCATION> Estonian </LOCATION> party, government and economic officials. `` It is necessary to seek what unites rather than divides,'' said <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, who was head of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> until September, when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appointed him to his present post. The growth of ethnic tensions in the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, as well as the southern republics of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> have become a severe test of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program of greater openness and economic reforms. Party and government officials in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> have joined activists in demanding greater economic and political autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Last week, they said in a meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that the Soviet leader's intended reform of the political system would take away many of their republic's rights rather than increase local control. On Monday, <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> assured Estonian leaders that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> was pleased more people were getting involved in public issues and gaining a stronger ethnic identity. But he said ethnic feelings were going too far. <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> told the Estonian officials `` the situation in the republic is characterized by a growing political tension,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. He described as especially alarming the division of the population along ethnic lines, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> on Friday, the same day two other Politburo members were sent to the Baltic on similar missions. <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> ideology chief, went to the republic of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Slyunkov </PERSON>, chief of social and economic development, visited the republic of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported the <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Slyunkov </PERSON> visits, but their speeches to officials were not as sharp as <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, where the reform movement has been the most active and organized.
