<TEXT>
 Millions of Brazilians voted today for mayors and city councilors in nationwide elections considered a popularity test of President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s beleaguered government. Some campaign workers were arrested for violating a law that prohibits campaigning within 100 yards of polling stations. They tried to hand out sample ballots with their candidate's name written in. However, no serious incidents were reported by early afternoon. People waitied patiently in lines up to four blocks long after polls opened at 8 a.m. -LRB- 5 a.m. EST -RRB-. They were to close at 5 p.m. -LRB- 2 p.m. EST -RRB-. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> voted in his home state of <LOCATION> Maranhao </LOCATION>, in far northern <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, then returned to <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>. Election results, not expected in full before Sunday, could indicate how Brazilians will vote next November in the first presidental elections in 29 years in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s biggest and most populous country. Voting is mandatory, and Brazilians who do n't vote face trouble getting a passport and obtaining a government loan or a civil service job. But polls show voter apathy is high. Campaigns urging voters to protest through voided ballots or to vote for nonsense candidates _ such as a popular chimpanzee in <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zoo </LOCATION> _ have attracted national attention. At stake are mayorships and council seats in 4,307 cities and towns. Campaigning by candidates from 29 parties has been unrestricted in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, which in 1985 returned to civilian government after 21 years of right-wing military rule. Parties ranged from Communist groups to supporters of the former military government. Although the voting is based largely on local matters, political analysts say Brazilians will also be voicing their opinion on <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s conservative-to-centrist Brazilian <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Polls indicate that the party _ which in 1986 swept elections for state governors, state assemblies and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ will be lucky to win the mayoral seats in three of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s largest cities. The governing party has been blamed for the soaring inflation and a 40 percent dip in workers' buying power. It has also faced charges of corruption and nepotism. Last week, soldiers killed three workers at the state-run <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in a clash with strikers. Protest signs at the workers' funerals said, `` Enough of <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>.'' Federal troops have been assigned to 207 cities in 13 states to maintian order during voting. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, a 58-year-old politician and poet, gained office as the running mate of <PERSON> Tancredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Neves </PERSON>, who was chosen in a military-controlled electoral college vote. <PERSON> Neves </PERSON> died shortly before taking office. The leading mayoral candidates according to Brazilian polls were: _ <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, the country's largest and richest city: <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Maluf </PERSON>, 57, wealthy industrialist and the defeated military-backed candidate for president in 1985 An appointed state governor and mayor under the military regime, <PERSON> Maluf </PERSON> belongs to the former regime's official <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. _ <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>, the second-largest city: <PERSON> Marcello </PERSON> <PERSON> Alencar </PERSON>, 63, a lawyer, journalist and former