<HEAD>China Shows Off Arms For Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> opened an international exhibit of its arsenal Tuesday complete with scale models and videos of the weapons in action. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Precision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the country's largest arms manufacturers, said it was putting six new missiles on the market during the four-day <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exposition </ORGANIZATION>, or Asiandex 88. They included several medium-range coastal defense missiles intended to replace the Silkworm, which Vice President <PERSON> Shen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rengui </PERSON> said used outdated technology and was being phased out. The Silkworm became <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous missile when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> used one in October 1987 to attack a Kuwaiti oil tanker flying the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> denied selling Silkworms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and said it did not know where <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> bought them. But Western experts said the new missiles and other weapons shown at <LOCATION> Asiandex </LOCATION> already were being promoted to potential buyers, and that the show contained no surprises. The exhibit demonstrated <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s determination to increase its arms sales despite criticism from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western countries that Chinese sales to primarily Third World countries are destabilizing. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> does not release figures on its arms sales, but the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government estimates <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> sold sold about $ 2 billion in weapons abroad in 1987. It i