<HEAD>Culture Minister Calls For Review of Dissident Policy, Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Slovak culture minister on Tuesday called on leaders to correct mistakes that have pushed people away from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and into the embrace of independent groups and churches. <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Valek </PERSON>'s unusually critical analysis of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s political situation was published by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper Rude Pravo He said the country's leaders must right mistakes made since the 1968 `` Prague Spring'' reforms were crushed. `` We must analyze the past period properly and expose errors and mistakes not only in the economy but also in politics,'' he wrote. `` On the one hand, there were anti-socialist and ... unrealistic tendencies. On the other hand, there were rational political and economic pressures, the need for reform, and those should have been seen and differentiated.'' <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> installed the conservative Czechoslovak leadership after the Aug. 21-22, 1968, invasion that crushed the reforms of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>. While embracing some economic reforms, it has been reluctant to follow <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s example in initiating wide-ranging political reforms. The Slovak official said the purge of 500,000 people from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was perceived, especially by the young, `` as an all-embracing condemnation of opposition, as a political trauma.'' This `` trauma ... has n't passed yet and is not going to pass all by itself.'' An analysis of the past was imperative, he said, to regain people's confidence. `` It is necessary to analyze continuously the cause of the birth and development of Charter 77'' human rights group, young people's apathy toward the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and increasing interest in religion, the minister said `` All these are facts to which realistic policy can neither surrender nor close its eyes naively,'' <PERSON> Valek </PERSON> wrote. The leadership's apparent unwillingness to re-evaluate the spirit of 1968 was highlighted by the police quelling of an Aug. 21 demonstration to mark the 20th anniversary of the invasion and official articles condemning <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> and his reforms. Last week, up to 25 activists were taken into preventive custody in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> to stop a symposium to examine <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s role in history. On Tuesday, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> strongly denounced Czechoslovak authorities for thwarting the symposium and served notice it will irrevocably block consensus on any <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> follow-up meeting in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. In a statement to the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting of the 35-nation <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> review conference on human rights, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> said, `` The contempt they -LRB- <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> authorities -RRB- displayed for the rights of Czechoslovak citizens amounts to contempt for the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting and the ... process in which <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> pledged to respect those rights.'' He said <PERSON> Czechoslovkia </PERSON>'s poor human rights record disqualified it from hosting a follow-up meeting. `` A prospective host should have a credible record on the subject to be discussed,'' he said. The Dutch <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> called in Czechoslovak Ambassador <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Chlad </PERSON> to condemn the crackdown as a `` violation of the fundamental principles of human rights,'' 