<FIRST>r a AM-Planetarium     11-15 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Planetarium,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Offering A Star-Studded Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A planetarium whose original projector made viewers dizzy and ill is opening nine years late with a 68-foot-wide dome and a projection system intended to simulate space travel. The Arnim D. Hummel Planetarium officially opens Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` I always thought it would actually happen, but I did n't think it would take as long as it did,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, who was hired 11 years ago as planetarium director. Equipment installed in 1979 projected images so blurred that people who watched test programs became dizzy and nauseated. The university sued the manufacturer of the projection equipment, <ORGANIZATION> Spitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chadds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. Two years ago, <PERSON> Spitz </PERSON> agreed out of court to replace the original equipment with a new system called Space Voyager In most planetariums, the same projector produces images of the stars and planets. That makes the planetariums `` Earth-bound,'' only able to project the sky as it appears from the Earth. With the Space Voyager system, the projectors are separated, making possible the illusion of space travel. The star-ball projector is 4 feet in diameter and projects 10,164 stars. Each star has a separate lens. There are five planet projectors and a sun projector. Also part of the system are a multiimage slide projector and a six-channel stereo sound system. The system is the third of its kind in the world. The others are in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. The planetarium is named for the first chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s physics department During World War II, <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> was instrumental in developing a radar-activated fuse. The university's planetarium is the 10th-largest of the 985 planetariums in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The largest is the Reuben H. Fleet Space Theater in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, which has a 75-foot dome.
