<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration today rejected a <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> proclamation of an independent Palestinian state, asserting that the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict must be settled by negotiations and not by unilateral acts. Spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the status of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> `` can not be determined by unilateral acts of either side but only through a process of negotiations.'' `` A declaration of independent Palestinian statehood is such a unilateral act,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. A similar statement was issued by <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that despite <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> opposition to the proclamation of an independent Palestinian state, the administration sees `` positive elements'' to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, most notably its support for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolutions 224 and 338. These lay the groundwork for a comprehensive settlement to the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the administration has not yet seen the final text of the resolution approved by the <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> but promised it would receive serious study. `` Our objective is a comprehensive peace,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` Direct negotiations must be at heart of the negotiating process. Palestinian partiicpation is required at every stage of negotiations. All participants in the negotiations must renounce terrorism and violence and each must agree on the accepted international basis of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolutions 224 and 338.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said it `` still is not clear just how specific'' the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has been about extending an olive branch to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by implicitly recognizing the Jewish state's right to exist. At the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> meeting, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s quasi-legislature voted to accept <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Resolution 242, which established the principle that all states in the region _ including <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ are entitled to exist in peace. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Monday that <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> acceptance of the resolution, which long has been the cornerstone of international efforts to secure a lasting peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, `` would be some progress.'' But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said `` there are other problems that remain to be solved'' before there is a breakthrough in the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s stance toward <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He was not more specific. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spoke before the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> proclaimed a new independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> as its capital. Apart from accepting the 1967 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy requires the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to renounce terrorism and to nullify the provision in its covenant calling for the destruction of the Jewish state. Otherwise, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are not supposed to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> or support its participation in any <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Monday released a `` fact sheet'' detailing attacks on Israelis attributed to the Popular Front for the Liberation of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. The group, which has its headquarters in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, is believed to have opposed approval of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. `` Apparently there has been an indication they're willing to abide by 242,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s approach to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution, adopted after the 1967 <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> war, that implicitly recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to live within secure borders `` I hope that is true because that would be some progress,'' he said during a picture-taking session in the Oval Office with <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the Soviet human rights activist. The resolution, which was adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> again in 1973, at the end of the Yom Kippur war, also calls on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to relinquish territory lost by the Arabs in 1967. Asked Monday whether an international peace conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> could represent a solution to the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> dispute, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> replied, `` I'm still not sure that that is the answer.'' Earlier this year, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cautiously supported efforts to arrange such a peace conference. However, officials stressed that any settlement depended on direct negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its Arab neighbors.
