<HEAD>Long-Lost Collection of Islamic Art Going on Display at Smithsonian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chance remark at a Parisian dinner party two years ago led to the discovery of a long-lost collection of rare Islamic art that will go on public display Sunday at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallery </PERSON>. The collection assembled by <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>, a turn-of-the-century jeweler and art collector in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, is `` perhaps the most important purchase in the history of the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McC </PERSON>. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. The 500 items in <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>'s collection of richly detailed paintings, manuscripts, calligraphies and bookbindings from ancient <LOCATION> Persia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and other major artistic centers of the <LOCATION> Near </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> were bought for $ 7 million. <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> officials say their real worth is much, much more, but that the collection is priceless in scope and quality. Drawn from the <PERSON> Vever </PERSON> collection are 150 items that will be displayed at the <LOCATION> Sackler </LOCATION>, many of them for the first time anywhere, from Sunday through April 30 in a show titled, `` A Jeweler's Eye: Islamic Arts of the Book from the Vever Collection.'' An hour-long `` Smithsonian World'' television special on <PERSON> Vever </PERSON> and his collection will be broadcast on public TV stations next March. <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>'s collection includes almost all of the great classical Persian texts, several important Arabic works and previously unknown manuscripts and paintings from major artistic centers of the Near East and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The art works, some dating to the 11th century, reflect the reverence for the written word in medieval Islam, stemming from the holy scriptures of the prophet <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> known as the Koran. The ruling elite built libraries of lavishly illuminated books and manuscripts as symbols of their cultural sophistication. <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>'s collection includes brilliant paintings in which the pigments were ground from minerals, precious stones and metals, an irresistible attraction to the jeweler and his contemporary, <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Cartier </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> officials say the only comparable collection in the world is housed at the <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beatty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Library </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>'s collection disappeared in the late 1930s during the German occupation of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vever </PERSON> himself died in 1942, and the whereabouts of his collection remained a mystery for nearly half a century. Then, during a small dinner party in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in November 1984, <PERSON> Laure </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Williamstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, found herself seated next to <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mautin </PERSON>, a wealthy, elderly sportsman and naturalized American, who casually disclosed a momentous secret. <PERSON> Mautin </PERSON> said he was <PERSON> Vever </PERSON>'s grandson and had inherited a major collection of Islamic art, which was shipped intact from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after World War II for safekeeping. There it remained, stored in a vault known only to <PERSON> Mautin </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON> telephoned the news to her son, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON>, curator of Near Eastern art at the Freer Gallery of Art and the yet-unbuilt <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON> gallery. <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON> was dumbfounded. He and <PERSON> Milo </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beach </PERSON>, now acting director of the <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON>, raced to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and won <PERSON> Mautin </PERSON>'s commitment to sell the collection to the Smithsonian. <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> were the first scholars to see the collection, by then moved to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, in 50 years. Among the well-preserved items hidden in trunks and stacked against walls was a surprise _ 39 full manuscripts previously unknown to scholars except for a handful that were exhibited in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in 1931. The $ 7 million purchase was financed by various Smithsonian trust and acquisition funds and private donors, including the late Dr. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON>, chief benefactor of the underground museum that opened in September 1987.
