 The woman sought in the deaths of seven elderly people whose bodies were dug up from the yard of her rooming house had told police she `` never killed anybody'' when she was questioned last week, court documents say. Police who found the sixth and seventh bodies in shallow graves Monday were expanding a search for bodies beyond the yard of the rooming house. Digging resumed this morning, and officers also searched the house. A warrant charging the boarding home's landlady, <PERSON> Dorothea </PERSON> <PERSON> Montalvo </PERSON> <PERSON> Puente </PERSON>, 59, with one count of murder was issued late Monday, said police Capt. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Somers </PERSON>. Police questioned her Friday, the day the first body was discovered, and released her Saturday morning for lack of evidence. `` Our first priority is to get her into custody,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said. According to sworn statements that police filed to obtain the warrant, <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> twice denied killing her missing tenants, saying, `` I have never killed anybody.'' But the affidavits said that one of her tenants, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, handed a detective a note that said, `` She's making me lie.'' Sharp later told police that one resident disappeared after he had caused a drunken ruckus and `` <PERSON> Dorothea </PERSON> told him that she would take him upstairs and make him better.'' About four days later, police said, <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> `` smelled a very strong odor of what he thought was death in the kitchen area.'' <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> told him the stench was caused by some faulty sewers. Investigators using shovels, steel probes and a tractor found the two bodies wrapped in cloth or clothes in the yard of the two-story Victorian house, said police Sgt. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>. The bodies found Monday, one unearthed in the front yard under a flower bed and the other in the side yard under a shed, are unidentified, like the five others. `` We'll continue to dig, and we wo n't stop digging until we've dug up every square inch of this yard,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said The arrest warrant charged <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> only with the slaying of <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON>, a mentally disabled transient who lived in the boarding house. A search warrant for the house was also issued Monday. The <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> Bee reported today that police in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> had been told <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> may be there. Investigators planned to excavate the rest of the yard at the rooming house and comb an adjacent lot that <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> gardened when it was vacant several years ago, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said. In 1982, <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> was convicted of drugging and robbing three people in a bar, and sentenced to five years in prison, authorities said. She was paroled after 2 -LCB- years, said <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>, a state <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. Police said they were uncertain about the cause of death or even the sexes of the victims found Monday. No cause of death was determined for the other victims, police said. The list of possible victims lengthened during the day. `` There are a lot more than eight names,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said, referring to the original list of occupants supplied by a social worker. `` There's a big list of names. We've got detectives scurrying all over this city.'' <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> also ran a board-and-care home up to nine years ago about eight blocks away. A separate team of investigators was interviewing tenants at that address but there were no immediate plans to dig there, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said. Police Lt. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Enloe </PERSON> said investigators believed the elderly victims were killed for their Social Security checks. Payments continued to be sent after the disappearances and someone else cashed the checks, he said. Police went to the house after neighbors reported a friend had been missing since August and a social worker said some of her clients were missing. A social worker familiar with the rooming house described the residents as elderly people on fixed incomes and with few relatives. The case worker, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickerson </PERSON>, told police <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> came to her in 1986, offering lodging. <PERSON> Nickerson </PERSON> said she took up <PERSON> Puente </PERSON>'s offer, and during the past two years referred 19 clients to <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> `` She was the best the system had to offer,'' <PERSON> Nickerson </PERSON> said. `` She said she was a widow and had a big house, and she said it was her time to give back to other people. ... That was her story and I did n't have any reason to doubt her.'' <PERSON> Puente </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, described her mother as someone who had a `` terrible childhood'' and was raised in orphanages. Bloom, of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, met her mother for the first time two years ago after being put up for adoption herself at birth. She said <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> was `` not animated at all'' and spoke in a monotone. On Sunday, police arrested <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCauley </PERSON>, a 59-year-old resident of the boarding house, on suspicion of being an accessory after the homicides. He was being held at the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jail. Authorities believe <PERSON> McCauley </PERSON> assisted <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> after the slayings, and that she may have arranged for others to dig the graves, police said.
