<HEAD>Authorities To Experiment with Radio Wave Toll Collection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new electronic toll system that will `` read'' a special automobile tag may help motorists whiz by toll booths, under an experiment planned by two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-area </LOCATION> authorities. The number of times a vehicle goes through the toll would be recorded by computer and a monthly bill charged to a credit card. The new system, called automatic vehicle identification or AVI, uses a radio frequency beam transmitter mounted in each lane that will read a unique serial number up to 20 digits from a tag mounted on each vehicle. A similar system now being experimented with in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> is working well, officials there said. The <ORGANIZATION> Triborough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tunnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> hopes to experiment with the new system at the <LOCATION> Verrazano-Narrows </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> _ a span between <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> that carries about 58 million vehicles a year _ beginning early next year, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> TBTA </ORGANIZATION>'s project manager for AVI, said Monday However, the experiment, which could cost up to $ 1.4 million, must first be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> TBTA </ORGANIZATION>'s parent agency. If approved, tags would be fitted on vehicles belonging to some trucking companies as well as vehicles belonging to <ORGANIZATION> TBTA </ORGANIZATION> employees and <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> buses that use the bridge, according to <ORGANIZATION> TBTA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which is experimenting with a similar system for buses at the <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tunnel </LOCATION>, plans to use the same trucking companies for its experiment at the <LOCATION> Goethals </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrastia </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The Goethals Bridge connects <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. In addition, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnpike </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thruway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION> are all committed to using the same AVI system. The decision to use the Verrazano-Narrows and <PERSON> Goethals </PERSON> bridges was made because `` a lot of the traffic would be the same,'' <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> said. Many long-distance truckers cross <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to avoid <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` The speed of proccessing at the toll booths is the main advantage'' of the system, <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON> said. `` It will reduce the need to handle cash, tickets and tokens.'' The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> transportation officials are optimistic about the system because of good results from a similar experiment in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnpike </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> that started last summer. `` It's coming along very well,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabler </PERSON>, a spokesman for the authority. The <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> experiment is being conducted on the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tollway </ORGANIZATION> and is currently limited to employees of <ORGANIZATION> AmTech </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, one of two companies that has developed the automated system. The Tollway is a heavily traveled, 20-mile-long highway between downtown <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and its northern suburbs.
