<HEAD>Reagan Calls Berlin Wall Litmus Test of East-West Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs graf 7, Kohl was meeting, with meeting occurring.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared the Berlin Wall `` a litmus test of East-West relations'' today as he held a farewell meeting with West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, responding through a translator at a departure ceremony on the White House lawn, thanked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for his efforts to improve relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Any kind of worsening in <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations will be felt like an earthquake in our country, and of course first of all in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who will leave office Jan. 20, said, `` The divided city of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> remains a powerful symbol of a divided <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and a litmus test of East-West relations.'' The two leaders, who have been close allies, exchanged personal best wishes along with discussion of issues. `` These have been good years,'' said <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. `` Both of us have paved the way for a development that will be pursued by your successor in office.'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> met with President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> later in the day at the vice president's residence. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meets with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, whom he said Monday he respects more than any other world leader he has met. Answering a question from a junior high school student as to whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would ever have a woman president, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he thought it was inevitable. `` As a matter of fact, the statesman in the world that I have met that I respect the most is the Prime Minister of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>,'' he said. `` And she's done a remarkable job for <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>.'' In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, columnist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Walden </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> wrote, `` We must brace ourselves for a Niagara of mutual admiration. The personal relationship has indeed been special.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> is scheduled to meet on Thursday with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who will be sworn in as president on Jan. 20. There have been reports from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that the prime minister would bring with her a proposal for an early meeting of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders. A senior administration official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said, `` We have nothing specific from the British in the course of planning this visit that said the prime minister would be bringing along a proposal of this kind, but we certainly would n't be surprised if such a proposal came.'' April 4 will be the 40th anniversary of the signing of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION>, and such decade anniversaries have been observed in the past by turning the annual spring ministerial meeting of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> into a heads of government meeting. `` We had heard that, as <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which is to be the site of the spring ministerial, considered planning for that spring ministerial in the 40th anniversary year, that some thought was being given to that meeting being a summit,'' the official said. The meeting will be in late May or early June. A West German official who briefed a reporter on condition of anonymity said <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s visit would enable him again `` to congratulate the president-elect and to see with him what the immediate tasks for both countries are.'' Both the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and West German officials said <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> was expected to discuss <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> relations with the president and to report on his own meetings with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> officials last month. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last met with both <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> at the seven-nation economic summit in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> last June. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> was last in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in February and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in July of 1987.
