<HEAD>Hamadi Becomes Ill, Testimony Interrupted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Confessed <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> hijacker <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> fell ill during his trial Tuesday, forcing the judge to interrupt emotional testimony by a former American hostage. The trial was adjourned until Monday after a doctor examined <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> and ruled the defendant was unable to follow the proceedings. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> flight 847, which was diverted on an Athens-to-Rome route and forced to land in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> told the court he was feeling `` very exhausted'' and `` very dizzy.'' The session was adjourned for nearly an hour while he was examined by a doctor, who told the court <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was suffering from dizzy spells and a headache. Circulation irregularities were blamed for the symptoms and <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was given a shot of glucose, said the doctor, who was not identified by the court. She said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> had been eating very little and taking medicine to counter low blood pressure. The session was interrupted during the testimony of <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, a 48-year-old American physician, who said he was returning from a vacation in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> with his wife and two daughters when the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> plane was seized. He described how he got up to go to a restroom and tried to find his wife among the passengers. `` I looked everywhere on the plane but she was n't there,'' <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said, his voice choked with emotion. `` First I thought she might have been killed, but then a stewardess told me she had been released from the plane,'' he said. Some of the passengers were released while the plane was in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> also testified how the hijackers robbed his wife of her jewelry, which he valued `` in excess of $ 50,000.'' <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said one of the hijackers `` lectured us on the evils of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and it went on and on.'' Like more than a dozen other American witnesses at the trial, <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> also described the brutal beatings of passengers by the hijackers. He said he had given a woman passenger an insulin shot, but that the hijackers had refused his request to examine two men who were severely beaten. `` They lay unconscious and looked dead. One had blood on his shirt,'' <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>'s 21-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Marypat </PERSON>, who testified earlier in the day, said she still suffers nightmares more than three years after the ordeal. `` I have had nightmares and I'm scared of flying on planes,'' she said. She also told the court she thought <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> directed the hijacking. `` I personally felt that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was more in charge and that he was the leader,'' she said. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> admits he was one of the hijackers but denies killing <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> or robbing the passengers. He says the hijacking was directed by his accomplice, fugitive <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON>, who is at large. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was arrested at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport in January 1987 when customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
