<HEAD>Upset Nationalist Poll Victory Reflects Scottish Disenchantment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A stunning election upset by <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s nationalists illustrates deepening Scottish dislike for the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> political establishment and could breathe new life into the campaign for independence Thursday's election in the <LOCATION> Govan </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION> was to fill a vacant seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, and since such by-elections are traditionally an occasion for registering protest votes, the result can not be accurately projected over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> as a whole. But it is a spectacular victory for the <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which seeks independence for <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, and a humiliation for the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the opposition in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> but the dominant force north of the English border. In one of the biggest upsets in 40 years of British politics, the <ORGANIZATION> SNP </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sillars </PERSON> won 14,677 votes aginst 11,123 for Labor's <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON>, a 38-percent swing from the June 1987 general election, when <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> took <PERSON> Govan </PERSON> by a massive 19,509-vote majority. It was almost a rerun of 1973, when <PERSON> Sillars </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Margo </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, staged a similar upset in Govan for the SNP. By the following year, after two general elections, the bandwagon effect had taken nationalist strength in the 650-member House of Commons from two seats to 11. By last year, however, the <ORGANIZATION> SNP </ORGANIZATION> was down to three seats. Now the question is whether the latest result is a freak, or the precursor of a 1970s-style revival. `` The Scottish people will now start marching towards their destiny as an independent country with an independent economy,'' <PERSON> Sillars </PERSON>, 51, declared to cheering supporters after the result was announced in the heavily blue-collar constituency. `` It's a pretty substantial blip,'' conceded Scottish Laborite <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Home </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>. He warned Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> that `` If she's not careful, and if this sort of bandwagon gets going, she could actually split up the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>.'' But the Conservatives, having harbored no expectations in <LOCATION> Govan </LOCATION>, felt little disappointment with their paltry 2,207 votes, preferring instead to mock <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s defeat. `` Last night must be the first by-election where the protest vote has been against the opposition rather than the government,'' taunted Tory government minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Forsyth </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s yen to end its 281-year-old union with <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> ebbs and flows. Right now, says Professor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellas </PERSON>, a political scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Glasgow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, `` there is a trend of Scottish nationalism rising.'' One reason is a widespread Scottish perception of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> as a thoroughly English prime minister with no understanding of Scottish concerns. `` There's a general feeling of Scottish interests being neglected by the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> government,'' <PERSON> Kellas </PERSON> said. Another reason is a new property tax that has provoked widespread hostility in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The poll tax, or community charge, will be calculated per head instead of on size of property, and is central to Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s crusade against left-wing local authorities who tax the well-off to finance welfare programs for the needy An opinion poll on election night found 21 percent saying the poll tax was the most important issue, compared with 19 percent who cited unemployment. The <ORGANIZATION> SNP </ORGANIZATION> seized the opportunity. Where Labor opted for legal, low-key opposition to the poll tax, the nationalists promised to organize a non-payment campaign. Thus, says <PERSON> Kellas </PERSON>, `` the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> appears powerless and does n't make enough impact. They're seen as playing the game according to the rules, through peaceful opposition within the confines of Parliament.'' He says there's no telling whether the <ORGANIZATION> SNP </ORGANIZATION> will capitalize on its triumph. Unlike in 1973, this time no general election is due for up to four years, and the afterglow of <PERSON> Govan </PERSON> may not last that long. But at the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> SNP </ORGANIZATION> believes it has found a winning formula _ `` independence within <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' That means an independent <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> living alongside <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and united with it through membership in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are talking about freeing <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> within the context of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, where <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> would be no more than a friendly partner and there would be no control of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> whatsoever,'' says <PERSON> Sillars </PERSON>. With the approach of 1992 and an end to tax barriers and frontier restrictions within the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, that notion `` is looking more palatable to people than in the past,'' said <PERSON> Kellas </PERSON>. Scottish social commentator <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Nairn </PERSON> said Scots who in the past would shy away from outright secession see the new formula as a way of retaining an association with <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> while going independent. `` The formula is appealing,'' he said, `` because it smacks of having your cake and eating it.''
