<HEAD>Bush Drew Support From GOP, Disaffected Voters, Survey Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, bgng: `In May,' to CLARIFY that ``him''
is
Bush</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the presidential election by solidifying his support with Republicans and successfully convincing disaffected voters to back him, according to a post-election survey released Tuesday. The poll, conducted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, also said 44 percent of the respondents thought the federal budget deficit should be the top priority for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Other crucial issues for voters are protecting American jobs and increasing programs for families and children. The telephone poll, one of several done for the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-based </LOCATION> news company in 1988, measured responses from 2,022 registered voters. The margin of error was three percentage points. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who defeated Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by 54 percent to 46 percent on Nov. 8, did not entirely recreate the coalition that gave President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a resounding victory in 1984, the poll found. But by the second week in September, the vice president had put together various elements that gave him a victory in November, the survey indicated. `` While our surveys showed a fair degree of offsetting change within Democratic groups between September and October, the overall patterns of support first identified in September persisted through Election Day,'' the pollsters said in a statement that accompanied the results. Among the trends reflected in the poll are that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: _ Bolstered support among core Republican groups between May and late October _ Increased support among young, moderate voters during the same period _ Seized the backing of disaffected voters, those lower-middle-income people who feel alienated and tend to be disgruntled `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could not have won with the disaffecteds,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON>, Gallup's president. That group is estimated to comprise about 10 percent of the voting pool. In May, shortly after the end of the primary season, the disaffecteds were evenly divided between <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. By September, their opinions of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had moved from lukewarm to highly critical. Ultimately, 68 percent said they voted for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the survey found. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Traugott </PERSON>, a Gallup analyst, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> attracted the disaffecteds by stressing his tough crime theme and pinning the liberal label on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. In fact, the success of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign was based on highlighting the controversies over liberalism, the Pledge of Allegiance and the prison furlough program. Among <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> voters, the most important campaign issues were the allegations about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s involvement in the Iran-Contra matter, the administration's dealing with <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the selection of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential candidate. Voters expressed some discontent with the campaign and the candidates, the survey said. Some 63 percent who backed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said they were dissatisfied with the candidates, while 16 percent of those who voted for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expressed dissatisfaction. Respondents also were asked to rate others participants in the political election. The news media and campaign consultants were given the lowest marks on an A through F rating system. One in six people gave the press a failing grade. <PERSON> Traugott </PERSON> said he thought the low grade given the press reflected in part a lack of understanding of how reporters do their work. Other surveys have shown, for instance, that the media as an institution is evaluated highly.
