<HEAD>Industrial Production Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production rose a moderately strong 0.4 percent in October, the best increase in three months, despite a decline in activity in the nation's oil fields, the government said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said its industrial production index last month rose to a seasonally adjusted 139.2 percent of its 1977 base, reflecting increases in production of business equipment and automobiles. `` We're not talking anything dramatic here, but it's a comfortable gain,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Noting that retail sales for the month also increased, <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> said, `` We're seeing strength in both the production side -LRB- of the economy -RRB- and the demand side, which suggests that strength on the production side can continue.'' The October gain in production at factories, mines and utilities was in line with economists' expectations. It followed smaller increases of 0.2 percent in September, revised up from an earlier estimate of no change, and 0.3 percent in August. Production jumped 1.1 percent in July. The index has not declined since September 1987, a reflection of the strength in the manufacturing sector. A drop in the value of the dollar has triggered a surge in sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods overseas this year and a related boom in spending to expand and modernize factories. However, economists have become worried that manufacturing may be growing too strongly, straining production capacity and leading to inflation. The relatively weak industrial production of August and September had calmed those fears somewhat, but signs of a rebound in October have rekindled the concern. `` What is needed is really rather subdued growth ... and that's not what we're getting,'' <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> said Production in the manufacturing sector rose 0.5 percent in October, following a 0.4 percent gain in September. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said automobiles were assembled at an annual rate of 7.6 million units, up from 7.4 million units a month earlier and 7.0 million units in August. Production of business equipment jumped 0.8 percent for the second month in a row and stood 9.4 percent higher than a year ago. Within that category, production of manufacturing equipment rose 1.8 percent last month and 1.9 percent in September. Output at mines, which includes oil and gas drilling, fell 0.9 percent in October, the third consecutive decline. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm, said falling world oil prices have curtailed drilling in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Over the last couple of weeks drilling activity has dropped off sharply. You're going to see that continue,'' he said. Production at utilities rose 0.4 percent last month, following a large drop of 3.8 percent in September, which was attributed to the decline in electricity use for air conditioners following the summer heat wave. Total output at factories, mines and utilities was 5.1 percent higher than a year ago.
