<SECOND>AM-Autism Report,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Legislative Committee Approves Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> must begin providing autistic children with the special education and attention their handicap demands, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee said in a report approved Tuesday. The House Select Committee to Study Autism voted unanimously to accept a draft report that outlines ways the state can help autistic children. There are about 15,000 autistic adults and children in the state, <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markosek </PERSON> estimated. The 32-page report will be put into bill form for introduction during next year's legislative session, <PERSON> Markosek </PERSON> said. The current legislative session ends Nov. 30. As defined in the report, autism is a mental disorder that is a `` severely incapacitating, lifelong developmental disability'' that usually appears from birth to age 3. Autistic children suffer from poor social relationships, impaired communication, and persistent repetitive and restrictive behavior, the report said. The state's failure to recognize autism as an illness different from other mental disorders results in autistic children being placed in educational courses that do not meet their needs, <PERSON> Markosek </PERSON> said. `` Since there are no formal categories, the children are placed in the category of being mentally retarded,'' he said, adding that `` a lot of times they get training that is inappropriate for them.'' <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Husic </PERSON>, a lobbyist for the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retarded </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, said because autism is not recognized as a separate disorder, autistic children are `` falling between the cracks.'' The report recommends developing in-service training programs on autism for professionals who deal with handicapped children, educating parents on ways to help their autistic children at home, and implementing programs to help the autistic move into regular classrooms, vocational training programs or the community. Also included in the report is a long-range recommendation that the state set up two regional centers for helping autistic children.
