<SECOND>AM-Church Sharing,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pastor Proposes Churches Share Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A minister is suggesting that various congregations could save money and reduce waste by joining forces to build a high-rise church, with one floor for each denomination and shared meeting areas. The Rev. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON>, pastor of <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of the Ascension in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, says such partner congregations could sell their land and put the money into a trust fund to help the needy. <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON>, 55, does n't propose all churches move in this direction. But he estimated that six churches within four miles of his church use their sanctuaries no more than 20 hours a week, and said the issue of under-used or wasted space needs to be considered. `` It is simply outrageous _ not to say un-Christian and a betrayal of the gospel _ that in those places where unfortunate people are most to be found, empty buildings and rarely used buildings are owned by people who call themselves by the name of <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, who himself had nowhere to lay his head,'' <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON> said. However, he said, `` Whenever I've shared it with other clergy, they've said, ` Yes, it is interesting, but it will never happen.' They just shrug it off.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cora </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Delmarva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecumenical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, who has worked as a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest in a shared church building in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said that sharing a building `` does promote ecumenism to some extent.'' `` It does n't solve all the problems, in the sense that people still want to be organized in groups small enough so they can know each other,'' <PERSON> Cora </PERSON> said. The Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, pastor of <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, said he hoped the proposal would be seriously explored. `` Part of me says it's important for historical reasons to maintain my church, but ... I would probably agree to it a little bit reluctantly to serve the greater good ...,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said. `` The most attractive part of it is you'd be able to spend more money on missions and not just on taking care of church property,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said.
