<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, calling each other `` Dear Ron'' and `` Helmut,'' bade their farewells on the sunlit South Lawn of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday after six years of close alliance on the world stage. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> reaffirmed `` the strong American commitment to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'' and said, `` That divided city ... remains a powerful symbol of a divided <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and a litmus test of East-West relations.'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> thanked the American president for his `` bold and resolute commitment to improving East-West relations'' and said, `` Any kind of worsening of the situation between East and West will by felt like an earthquake in our country ... and, of course, first of all in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>.'' It was an unseasonally balmy day, and even warmer weather is forecast for Wednesday, when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> holds a similar meeting with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. Neither <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> broke any new ground in their meeting or the formal departure statements that followed it. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that the two countries `` continue to seek ways to share early the risks, burdens and responsibilities, as well as the benfits, of our common defense.'' `` We reviewed the difficulties each country faces in doing more, but pledge we would each do our fair share,'' the president said. He congratulated <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> on the decision of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> member states to take steps toward closer economic integration by the end of 1992 and expressed `` our concern that this be done in a manner that promotes fair trade internationally.'' They devoted much of their closing statements, however, to reminiscence and farewell. `` Helmut, this marks my last meeting as president with you,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Six years ago, we stood together as I announced the formation of a presidential commission to commemorate the tricentennial of the first German settlement in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Six years to the day, I'm proud to announce a product of that commission _ the dedication of a garden, here in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, as a symbol of the friendship between our two countries.'' `` In a few months, I ` ll be leaving the White House,'' he said. `` But, the garden _ and all it represents _ will remain, to be nurtured and sustained by the friendship between Germans and Americans and by the leadership that you have provided.'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, speaking through an interpreter, told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, `` I believe we can say, Mr. President, <PERSON> Dear </PERSON> <PERSON> Ron </PERSON>, we can put it very briefly and say these have been good years. I think that both of us have paved the way for development which will be pursued by your successor in office. ... God bless you in all you do.''
