<HEAD>Doctors Weigh Whether To Separate Siamese Twins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A doctor who delivered Siamese twins said his first indication of the unusual birth was the sight of three arms emerging from the incision he made for a Caesarean section. `` On the fetal monitor, there was only one heartbeat and it was perfect. The baby appeared to be of normal size. There was no fetal distress,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, the obstetrician-gynecologist who delivered the twins Sunday at <ORGANIZATION> Frederick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Shortly after birth they were brought to <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. `` We were expecting one baby, not two babies joined together at the chest and upper abdomen,'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said. When <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> made the incision, `` Three arms came out and I knew definitely that something was going on,'' he said. `` I also knew the first incision would not work. The baby was trapped. I was afraid we might damage the baby.'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said he quickly made another incision. `` We could see the baby was not in good shape _ its color was poor, it was lethargic and not breathing well,'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said. `` Then, I had a very big, astonishing surprise. We did n't have one baby. We had two that were conjoined. After I calmed down, I did my surgery.'' Siamese twins, which result when a fertilized egg fails to divide completely, occur once every 50,000 to 100,000 live births. About half of such twins die within 48 hours of birth. The parents, who live in <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> and have one other child, have asked that their names and details of the twins be withheld, including their sex and whether dcotors will try to separate them. `` I think the parents are still in shock,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrop </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. `` It will be a couple of days before our physicians can say whether we can do anything for the babies.'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said he did not perform a sonogram, or ultrasound test, which can detect multiple pregnancies, physical abnormalities and determine fetal age, because the mother did not want one. In March 1982, Siamese twins joined from the chest to the abdomen were successfully separated in a 10-hour operation at <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. And 14 months ago, <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> made medical history when <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON> of Ulm, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, became the first Siamese twins ever to survive separation at the head.
