<HEAD>Researcher Modifies Bacteria to Protect Crops From Frost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed for release by source until 6:45 EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Potato seedlings treated with a genetically modified bacteria designed to protect plants from frost damage suffered one-third as much damage as unprotected plants, a researcher reported Tuesday. Two years of small-scale field tests proved the procedure to be safe and effective, according to <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON>, associate professor of plant pathology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>'s College of Natural Resources <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON> was scheduled to report his findings Tuesday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phytopathological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. Similar research by other scientists has shown that genetically modified bacteria can protect strawberry plants from frost. The minor genetic modification was designed to counter the effect of common bacteria whose structure triggers frost formation on plants at temperatures just below freezing. <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON> and an associate genetically modified a strain of the bacteria so it lacked the frost-promoting gene but was otherwise unchanged. The modified bacteria was applied to potato seedlings before naturally occurring bacteria could gain hold. Monitoring showed that the modified bacteria could not be detected beyond the experiment's 93-foot buffer zone <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON>'s field tests were delayed for almost four years because of safety concerns about outdoor experiments using genetically engineered organisms. But <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON> said the genetically altered bacteria `` wo n't thrive outside of the treated area'' because other bacteria are established there. Established frost-fighting methods such as sprinklers and wind machines can be more effective but they work in a narrower temperature range and are more expensive to administer than the bacteria strategy, <PERSON> Lindow </PERSON> said.
