<HEAD>Carlucci To Seek More Funds for Military Coporate Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, warning that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s security in the next century will depend upon advanced research being performed now, said Tuesday he wanted to increase by $ 300 million the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s support of independent corporate research. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, in a speech at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said he had been reviewing <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending on `` independent research and development'' and that despite the national budget deficit, could not support cuts in such spending. `` This independent <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; D program allows corporations full flexibility in determining what research and development to conduct, while at the same time enabling the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to identify emerging technologies judged to have important defense applications,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` In 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reimbursed contractors for $ 3.6 billion of the more than $ 7 billion they spent on <ORGANIZATION> IR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; D. As a measure of this program's effectiveness, I want to announce today that I will submit a 1990 budget request to the president allotting an additional $ 300 million to underwrite independent R & amp; D.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> described the move as one of four key steps to maintaining <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s technological lead over the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in military weaponry. The other steps include maintaining effective controls against technology theft and espionage; more cooperation with Western allies who also are pushing back technological frontiers; and supporting a healthy defense industrial base of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contractors. In his speech, a copy of which was released in advance at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> expressed optimism about each of the four steps except one: the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial base. `` This, I am sorry to say, is at present a dark cloud on the strategic horizon,'' he said. `` There are unmistakable signs that right now, our defense industrial base is shrinking _ the result of a defense budgeting process and acquisition system that combine chronic instability and excessive regulation, with predictable results. `` We need to put an end to this erosion; streamline and stabilize the system, and create a more hospitable climate for technological innovation and growth.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is expected to step down in January when Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is inaugurated as president and thus the fate of his recommendation for increased research spending remains unclear. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had been widely rumored in recent months to be considering a cut in such funding and thus <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s endorsement of an actual increase might carry great weight with his successor. Earlier in his speech Tuesday, delivered before the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> at the university, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> asserted technology had made it possible for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` to meet its national security needs without militarizing society.'' `` Rather than engaging in a contest to match potential adversaries soldier for soldier, ship for ship or tank for tank, we have sought to turn our technological superiority to our strategic advantage. To a large extent, we've offset quantity with quality,'' he said.
