<FIRST>u a AM-L'Ambiance-Settlement Bjt   11-15 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-L'Ambiance-Settlement, Bjt,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>$41 Million Settlement Reached in L'Ambiance Plaza Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Families of 28 men killed in the L'Ambiance Plaza building collapse and the 16 men who were injured will share $ 30 million under a tentative $ 41 million settlement of all lawsuits, a judge said Tuesday. Legal experts said the mediation process that led to the agreement may have averted years of litigation and was unique because of the number of lawsuits and potential lawsuits involved. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> said he and a state <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge, who together mediated talks leading to the settlement, scheduled a hearing for final approval of the agreement for Dec. 1. If all parties sign, it would end all litigation from the collapse of the half-finished apartment building in <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> on April 23, 1987. `` I think we have a global settlement of all aspects of the L'Ambiance building collapse and I feel very, very good,'' <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> said. `` All 40 defendants and potential defendants contributed -LRB- to the settlement -RRB-, which speaks of extraordinary cooperation.'' `` No amount of money is going to replace what those people lost. The only good thing is that it was done speedily,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieder </PERSON>, lead counsel for the plaintiffs. The proposed settlement did n't resolve the question of who was to blame, although federal investigators placed the primary blame for the accident on three contractors. Lawyers for all sides are reviewing documents drafted to implement the settlement. Federal, state and probate judges, along with two members of the state <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Compensation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, also will be asked to approve it, <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> said. Under the settlement, the children of the men who died will receive a weekly income until they are 30 years old and money for college if they choose to go, <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> said. The mediators wanted them to be taken care of `` just as if their fathers had lived,'' he said. Widows will receive income from annuities until they are 62 to 65 years old, when they will be eligible for Social Security, <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> said. Individual payments to victims and their heirs were n't released. Several legal experts commended the mediation process <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> and state Judge <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meadow </PERSON> organized. There were 92 attorneys involved representing victims' families and workers, 40 companies involved in the project, the city of <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> and state and federal agencies. `` It's working concurrently to wrap the whole thing up in one package that seems to me to be quite unusual and commendable,'' said J.L. <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON>, adjunct professor of law at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` What is -LRB- unusual -RRB- is the size and scope of this case and the potential number of parties and complexity of it,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and a <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION> attorney. <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> and <PERSON> Meadow </PERSON> determined how much each victim should receive by considering such factors as the age and health of the deceased or injured, past wage history, earning capacity, age and income of heirs, severity and degree of personal injuries, and life expectancy. In addition to the $ 30 million for the workers and their families, the proposed settlement provides $ 11.25 million to settle other claims, including those of contractors and insurance carriers against one another, and to be used as reserve funds. A portion of the $ 30 million would be invested in annuities, which are expected to generate an additional $ 20 million. The tentative settlement also includes provisions for the rebuilding of L'Ambiance Plaza and the distribution to the plaintiffs of some profits from the building for an undetermined number of years. Still unresolved are $ 5.1 million in proposed federal fines against five companies that worked on the project and accusations that they violated federal safety rules. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikelson </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said, `` I can confirm that <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> is in discussion with the court on a possible settlement. There is no agreement at this point.'' <PERSON> Zampano </PERSON> and <PERSON> Meadow </PERSON> said in their report that if <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> demands full payment of fines from the five companies, it could `` affect seriously the contributions to the settlement fund.''
