<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In asking <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to stay on as <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has turned again to a long-time personal friend to staff a key Cabinet post. Last week, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced as his first Cabinet appointment his choice of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> to be secretary of state. While <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is the better known because of his service with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> is just as close to the president-elect. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and another close <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> friend, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> oil millionaire <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, were dubbed the Big Three in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presidential campaign _ the longtime friends whose counsel <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> listened to most often. There is speculation that <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> may become <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> secretary. With <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s support, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, 58, got the nod from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to become <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary when <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> announced in August that he was leaving the administration to formally become chairman of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presidential campaign. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> was sworn in as the nation's 68th <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary on Sept. 15. In his first two months, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has adopted a low-key approach which emphasized keeping the economy on track and avoiding any controversy that might stir up financial markets before the Nov. 8 election. With the election over, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> is expected to mov