CATION> and other countries will force the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to acknowledge next year that more needs to be done in the area of debt forgiveness. Events are also likely to force <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to quickly address the savings and loan crisis, where estimates of the cost of bailing out hundreds of insolvent institutions have skyrocketed to between $ 50 billion and $ 100 billion. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has already appointed a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> task force to study the problem. Another <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> study group is looking at the capital gains tax and this too is likely to be a priority in the new administration. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaigned on a pledge to cut the capital gains tax, which is levied on profits from the sale of stocks, real estate and other investments. The top rate is 33 percent, the same as for salary income, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed cutting it to 15 percent, prompting the charge from Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that such a cut represented a giveaway to the rich. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has discussed capital gains tax-reduction proposals with top aides and reportedly favors the idea of a `` sliding-scale'' tax that would allow the rate to decline the longer the asset had been held. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> is a millionaire whose upbringing and <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> education closely resemble those of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. He entered <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> one year after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> graduated. He went on to get a masters degree in business at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and then became an investment banker in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, spending an entire career since 1954 at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORG