<FIRST>u w AM-Wetlands     11-15 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wetlands,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends Major Overhaul of Wetlands Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government-sponsored panel of diverging interests on Tuesday recommended a major overhaul of wetlands protection, with states assuming responsibility for a national goal of creating more wetlands than are being destroyed. The National Wetlands Policy Forum, convened by the <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> at the request of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposed goal of ending the conversion of wetlands to other uses did not mean every single parcel of marshy ground would have to be preserved, but enough wetlands should be created or restored to outweigh the losses. `` The federal government has hundreds of wetlands rules, but there is no guiding principle, no overriding goal,'' said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>, who served as chairman of the forum. `` The result is confusion equal to rush hour on the beltway.'' The 20-member forum embraced representatives of builders, industry, environmental groups, state and local governments and federal agencies. Its recommendations were presented as a consensus package, and <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> and others said the group would oppose attempts to pick out particular measures from the more than 100 recommendations to support or oppose. About half the 200 million acres of marshes and bogs, fens, swamps and other wetlands that were present in the lower 48 states when European settlement began have been converted to other uses _ farms, housing developments, shopping centers, airports and everything else that humans do. In recent decades, though, environmental benefits of wetlands have been recognized increasingly: storage of flood water, cleansing of pollution, protection of wildlife, spawning and nursing of 60 percent to 90 percent of the nation's commercial fish catch, recharging groundwater and controlling erosion. A major study in the 1970s estimated that losses over the two previous decades had proceeded at 400,000 acres _ half the size of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> _ to 500,000 acres per year. No one knows if that still holds true. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> uses 350,000 acres and a recent congressional study used 275,000 acres. Among major recommendations of the forum: _ A national agricultural wetlands reserve which would pay farmers to transfer land or easements to wetlands preservation trusts These trusts would operate somewhat like the Nature Conservancy and other private groups to hold reserved land. The reserve should aim to protect 5 million existing acres and restore half as much, the forum said. _ Each state should enact wetlands protection plans which, if approved by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, would qualify the state to take over many, though not all, of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s wetlands protection jobs Only <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> has taken over <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> wetland regulation tasks so far. _ States with approved programs might be able to issue `` regional general permits which would allow the conversion of a limited amount of ecologically low value wetland areas in exchange for full compensatory mitigation. _ Federal activities would have to be consistent with approved state plans, just as they now must be in states with approved <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> plans _ `` Regulatory authorities should take any necessary action, including amending existing regulations, to prevent the willful alteration of wetland characteristics to circumvent regulatory jurisdictions.'' _ Make the definitions of wetlands uniform Some 50 different definitions of wetlands are in use throughout the federal government. _ A major effort to identify public lands where wetlands could be restored, with priority attention to the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast's `` extremely high wetlands losses from erosion and subsidence, largely as a result of government flood control and other water resource projects The report noted, `` The fact that the protection of wetlands makes good economic as well as environmental sense for society but not necessarily for the individual owning them is central to much of the conflict over wetlands protection policies,'' and a conservative advocacy group singled out that point as one weakness. `` Property owners have a right to develop their property,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivett </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, adding that `` there is no mention in this report of the Fifth Amendment problem.'' He referred to court rulings that some land use regulations can be so burdensome as to amount to a `` taking'' of property for public use that requires compensation to the owner under the Constitution's Fifth Amendment <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hookano </PERSON> of the foundation said the group believes major wetlands need protection, but he said the report does not go beyond recommendations of the regulatory task force chaired by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in 1982. `` It's irresponsible to recommend a program without a price tag,'' he said, arguing that the agricultural wetlands reserve could cost billions of dollars. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, whose leaders took part in the study, endorsed the report, but one environmental group that did not participate said it had `` serious concerns about delegating authority to the states'' because state and local governments were more vulnerable to pressure from development interests than the federal government.'' <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Malakoff </PERSON> of Friends of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> said, `` We're suspicious of state control. We're not sure the states have the resources to regulate in this area.''
</TEXT>
