<SECOND>AM-Economy-Glance,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Markets Anxiously Await Trade Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The financial markets were hoping for good news Wednesday with the release of the merchandise trade balance for September. Most economists expect a decline in imports to narrow the trade gap to $ 10.5 billion from the $ 12.2 billion August deficit. If the deficit exceeds that amount, market analysts fear it could trigger a selloff in the dollar, stock and bond markets. Meanwhile, there were these developments in the economic picture Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 12.09 points to 2,077.17 in a particularly slow session, reflecting widespread reluctance to participate ahead of the monthly trade report.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RETAIL SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales rose 0.9 percent in October to a seasonally adjusted $ 135.6 billion, the strongest increase in seven months. Sales figures are not adjusted for inflation and many of the increases can be attributed to higher prices. For the first 10 months of the year, overall sales were up 6.1 percent over the same period of 1987, barely keeping ahead of the inflation rate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.4 percent in October, the strongest increase in three months. It followed smaller increases of 0.2 percent in September and 0.3 percent in August, and a big jump of 1.1 percent in July.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TREASURY SECRETARY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> named <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to remain in his current post in the new administration. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> both reassured investors recently that the new administration had no secret plan to drive down the value of the dollar after the currency's value fell sharply due to uncertainty over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s economic policies.
</TEXT>
