<SECOND>AM-Oyster Creek,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Reports ``Unusual'' Reactor Water Flow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORKED RIVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Slightly radioactive water spilled at the <LOCATION> Oyster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> nuclear plant Tuesday, forcing officials to declare the lowest of four emergency categories. Nobody was contaminated and no injuries were reported, said plant spokesman <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Polon </PERSON>. The water spilled onto a reactor floor when a seal that is normally used to cap the flow failed during maintenance, <PERSON> Polon </PERSON> said. About six employees were working on the device when the water spilled. The accident prompted declaration of an `` unusual event,'' because water flow exceeded the normal 25 gallons per minute, <PERSON> Polon </PERSON> said, estimating the flow at between 25 and 50 gallons per minute. The declaration, the lowest of four emergency categories, began at 2:40 a.m. and ended at 4:30 a.m., <PERSON> Polon </PERSON> said. About 10,000 gallons of water were collected before repairs were completed, <PERSON> Polon </PERSON> said. The water went into the plant's drainage system, where it was recirculated. <LOCATION> Oyster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> has been shut down since Sept. 29 for maintenance and refueling. There is no fuel in the reactor.
