<HEAD>Refugees Welcome Declaration of Independent State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinian refugees outside the Israeli-occupied territories welcomed the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> declaration of a new state Tuesday, but some criticized the implied recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` I'm as happy as if I had won millions of dinars,'' said 23-year-old <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Salhi </PERSON>, whose family fled to the Al-Hussein refugee camp in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Lydda </LOCATION> in what is now <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dhabi </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> emirate, teacher <PERSON> Irtifaa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gameel </PERSON> <PERSON> Khateeb </PERSON> said: `` It's lovely to hear the term <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state.. but the Palestinian is still being beaten up'' in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. More than 300 Palestinians have been killed and thousands wounded since an uprising against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation began in the occupied lands Dec. 8, 1987. One of more than 300,000 Palestinians who live in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, economist <PERSON> Tewfik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Latif </PERSON>, called the declaration `` a good political step that represents an embarrassment to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They should now prove their good intentions.'' He referred to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refusal to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> until it endorsed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolution 242, which implies acceptance of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and renounced terrorism. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, meeting in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, proclaimed a Palestinian state with <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> as its capital and endorsed the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution while stressing Palestinian rights to self-determination. It also said guerrilla actions against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would be limited to military targets in the occupied territories, where the Palestinian state presumably would be established. The council serves as the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> legislature. Some pessimism was evident. `` I think the Americans will not recognize the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> regardless of what concessions we extend,'' said businessman <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. `` They will now say what the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> did is inadequate, we want more.'' A dentist at the Al-Hussein camp, <PERSON> Bassam </PERSON> <PERSON> Khadra </PERSON>, said: `` As a political step it means the recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and we reject that.'' His family is from Safad in what is now <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> groups opposed to <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said the declaration was `` dangerous'' and threatened the unity of Palestinians involved in the uprising. In the <PERSON> Jebel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> district of <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Saadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Dabbour </PERSON>, a physician from a Safad family, served Palestinian sweets to visitors at his clinic to celebrate the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> announcement. <PERSON> Dabbour </PERSON> said he was `` full of happiness. ... I have been waiting for this for four decades.'' Asked about recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he said: `` It is an evil that we can not avoid.'' <PERSON> Abdul-Munim </PERSON> <PERSON> Subeihi </PERSON>, a butcher in the Al-Hussein camp, said his family fled <LOCATION> Lydda </LOCATION> in 1948 and he will return someday. `` I was prosecuted -LRB- in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> -RRB- ... on charges of smuggling weapons to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I will go back -LRB- to <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> -RRB-. ... I am very happy. There is something now I can depend on.'' <PERSON> Shukri </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON>, a taxi driver who came to <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>'s Nuzha camp from <LOCATION> Jaffa </LOCATION> in 1968, said: `` All the people I drove today said they are celebrating the new beginning, a bright one, the Palestinian state. Long live Palestine.'' About 26,000 refugees are crowded into Al-Hussein camp, on the slope of a hill in the Jordanian capital. Scores of children played in front of simple concrete houses along narrow dirt lanes that intersect the main paved road through the camp. The main road was lined with stalls for the weekly vegetable market and customers crowded around them. More than 100,000 registered refugees live in five official camps in the <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> area, and at least 100,000 more live in five camps in northern <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> has about 800,000 registered Palestinian refugees.
