 PLO </ORGANIZATION> must forswear all terrorist activities, among other conditions. The administration was more ambivalent in its attitude toward the outcome of the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> meeting than was <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, whose Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> ruled out all negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> `` because they are opposed to peace with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said it was not clear whether the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> initiative constituted an olive branch to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> added to the confusion about future steps with his response to a question on whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was ready to talk with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's under consideration. We do not know exactly what is in the agreement,'' he said. That statement went far beyond what his official spokesmen were willing to say but it was not clear whether <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> understood the question, which a reporter shouted at him at the conclusion of a departure ceremony on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawn </LOCATION> of the White House for visiting West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> quickly amended <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remark by saying, `` What he was referring to was the meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and the fact that we would have to consider and we are considering the results of those meetings, but that we have reached no decisions on them.'' Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, wrote a letter to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urging him to withhold recognition of the <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> decisions and to encourage <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies to do the same. `` The declaration falls short of the statutory standard'' set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy since 1975, as well as a bill passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> several years ago, states that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> `` must expressly recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> decision does not do so, <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> added.
