<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Negotiators Reach Tentative Agreement on Namibian Independence,
Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Negotiators reached tentative agreement Tuesday on a plan that will bring Namibian independence from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in early 1989 and a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> over a 27-month period, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. The agreement was worked out during five days of negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> involving officials from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. It is subject to final approval by their respective governments. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, insisting on anonymity, said current plans call for the formal agreement to be signed in early December. The accord was mediated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>. The plan calls for implementation, starting in February, of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution designed to end <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 73-year rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last colony Under the plan, elections for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s first independent government will be held in August and the new regime will take office in early 1990, the officials said. A second part of the agreement envisions the withdrawal of two-thirds of the more than 50,000 Cuban troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> during the one-year period ending in December 1989. The agreement also calls for the gradual redeployment of remaining Cuban troops northward, away from the Namibian border and from the stronghold of anti-communist Angolan rebels backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, no details were disclosed but <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s chief negotiator, <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerden </PERSON>, said, `` All parties have agreed to take a document home to their governments.'' He said the document would be the basis for a final agreement `` if the parties accept it.'' <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> first sent troops to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in 1975 to help the fledgling independent government, newly freed from <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> colonial rule, fend off military incursions from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> which was concerned about communist penetration of the region. With the exception of a residual force, all the Cubans will be back home by early 1991 under the timetable agreed to in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. Left unanswered is the fate of the U.S.-backed rebel movement, known by its Portuguese initials, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has been the principal supplier of the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> forces for years, ferrying equipment across the Namibian border to the rebel stronghold in southeast <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. But with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> apparently intending on removing its forces from <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, that country will no longer be able to continue its resupply operation because of logistical problems. President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> will continue, but <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials have indicated that the South African resupply role can not be duplicated. On the other hand, the officials said that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has played an indispensable role in supporting the Angolan Army and that the removal of the Cuban troops will shift the military balance in <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s favor. <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> has sought to bring an end to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s internal conflict by calling for national reconciliation negotiations between <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government and the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebels But the Angolan government has rejected negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, calling instead on the rebels to lay down their arms and join in a national reconstruction effort.
