<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators on Tuesday called for an immediate review of air traffic control procedures in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> after finding that a string of errors allowed a commuter plane to fly alarmingly close to <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One last month. The incident, which had been reported previously without detail, occurred Oct. 12 when Air Force One with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> aboard and a <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> commuter plane flew within 500 feet vertically and 1.5 miles horizontally as both planes were preparing to descend to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> Standard separation for aircraft is 1,000 feet vertically and five miles horizontally. At the time of the incident, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> officials said the president was never in danger. But the incident prompted a broad investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> which said Tuesday that `` numerous managerial, operational and training deficiencies'' at four <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> facilities near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and near <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> were at fault. These errors reflected `` a serious lack of effective management and quality assurance,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>. It called on the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to conduct an independent investigation of air traffic control performance at the facilities involved similar to a probe recently concluded after a series of controller errors at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The board also said it was particularly concerned about its findings because the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> on a number of occasions dating back to l986 had investigated similar shortcomings at the facilities and indicated improvements had been made. `` The seriousness and magnitude of the problems ... justifies the highest level of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> attention and action,'' the five board members said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said the agency would have no immediate comment on the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> findings. Among the findings that raised the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s concerns were: _ The controller at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> air traffic control center near <LOCATION> Leesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who was handling the Bar Harbor plane, was never aware that Air Force One was in the same vicinity as the commuter in airspace between <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> _ A senior controller who was handling Air Force One was not clear on airspace boundaries and allowed <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One to penetrate the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> center airspace handled by the controllers near <LOCATION> Leesburg </LOCATION> _ A directive to hold up traffic into <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> because of the impending arrival of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One was misunderstood because the message was not specific regarding which route Air Force One was using _ Two controllers who observed <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One and the commuter plane converging did not raise an alarm because they assumed there were plans already made to resolve the potential conflict _ An area supervisor involved indirectly in the incident was found to have been `` assigned to a position for which he was untrained and uncertified'' while another air traffic coordinator was given duties `` without receiving formal on-the-job training or a briefing on his responsibilities. The board said these and other shortcomings `` contributed directly or indirectly to this incident.'' As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> said, a controller at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> air route center gave the <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> commuter pilot permission to descend from 11,000 feet to 7,000 feet, while another controller at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> air traffic control center cleared <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One to descend from 11,000 feet to 9,000 feet. Both planes were converging toward roughly the same area. The two planes were allowed to continue to converge until another controller noticed the two aircraft and directed the commuter to halt his descent at 10,000 feet and directed it away from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> aircraft, the safety board said. At one point, two other air traffic controllers, whose primary responsibility was to monitor traffic flow, `` realized there was a potential conflict when the radar targets, representing <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One and the commuter plane were about 10 miles apart and at about the same altitude,'' the investigators said. But the two controllers, who were not directly handling either of the planes, `` did not initiate a -LRB- warning -RRB- ... because they believed that some type of separation standard was going to be achieved.'' When the incident occurred, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was on a campaign trip on behalf of Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. He had spoken near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and was headed for <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> for another appearance. During the trip, officials advised reporters of the incident but provided no details and emphasized that <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One was never in danger of a collision. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the president was not aware of the incident until later. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said that the pilot of Air Force One had been advised that the Bar Harbor commuter plane was nearby and no evasive action was required. Bar Harbor aircraft was flying as <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> Flight 3494 and carried 33 passengers and three crew members on a flight from <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>.
