<HEAD>Likud Asks Labor To Join Government As Junior Partner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc asked the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday to join a coalition government as junior partner, but both sides indicated there were too many policy differences. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and Labor, which leans to the left, spent four years as equal partners in a tenuous `` national unity'' coalition after indecisive elections in July 1984. In parliamentary elections Nov. 1, Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> won 40 seats in the 120-member <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION> and Labor, led by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, got 39. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has been negotiating with small right-wing and religious parties. On Monday, President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> asked him to form a government. During a 90-minute meeting Tuesday, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said Labor could join a government under his leadership only if it dropped its insistence on an international <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> did not respond publicly to the demands, but <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said Labor ministers in the caretaker <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> opposed a coalition under such conditions. After two weeks of negotiations, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> is in a position to form a majority coalition with four religious parties and three from the extreme right. His offer to Labor was seen as an attempt to avoid growing demands from those potential partners. `` I explained to Labor that the good of the country demands the establishment of a broad-based government, a government which would include the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> and those parties that expressed a willingness to join a government under my leadership,'' the prime minister said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television. `` We have heard an invitation,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said. `` Some things were more explicit, some things were more open-ended. We will discuss it and then decide.'' The 4-year-old coalition, in the first half of which <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was prime minister and <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> foreign minister, has been split on how to achieve peace with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations and end the 11-month-long Palestinian uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> refuse to trade occupied land for peace, have called for increased military measures to end the <LOCATION> Palestiinian </LOCATION> revolt and oppose an international conference, which the Arabs demand. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are willing to exchange some of the occupied land for peace and favor an international conference. <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Modai </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> said: `` The question is do we have a common approach on basic issues. After glancing at <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s election platform, I would have to say no.''
