<HEAD>Brazilians Vote in Local Elections Seen As Test For Sarney</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with exit polls showing
Sarney's party losing badly; PICKS up 5th pvs: More than...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Brazilians voted Tuesday in municipal elections seen as popularity test for President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s government. Exit polls showed the government trailing badly, a television network said. At stake were mayoralties and city legislatures in 4,307 cities and towns in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s biggest country. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> has been widely blamed for the country's economic stagnation, inflation approaching 2,000 percent a year and a 40 percent drop in workers' buying power. Exit polls showed the government party leading in just six of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 24 state capitals, according to <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globo </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest private network In 1985 mayoral and city council elections, the same party took 17 major cities. Pre-election polls showed <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s Brazilian <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ which in 1986 swept elections for state governors, state assemblies and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ will be fortunate if it wins even three mayorships in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 14 largest cities. More than 75 million registered voters were to choose from 1.2 million candidates belonging to 29 parties, ranging from two communist groups to supporters of the former military regime. Lines at polling places were four city blocks long in many cities. Some results were expected late Tuesday, but officials said final results probably would not be announced until Sunday. Voting is mandatory, and Brazilians who do n't vote face trouble getting a passport, obtaining a government loan or a civil service job. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, the first civilian president since a 21-year military regime ended in 1985, called the elections a `` step toward democracy.'' `` Do n't think democracy is easy ... To be a democrat, it's necessary to renounce violence and convince by ideas and choose by the ballot,'' the president told a nationwide television audience Monday night But recent polls showed voter apathy and distrust of politicians were high. In <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>, many Brazilians took advantage of the national holiday and the warm weather to crowd the city's famous beaches, leaving voting for later. In recent weeks, a campaign begun by a satirical newspaper to `` elect'' a chimpanzee in the Rio Zoo as mayor has gained national attention as a sign of Brazilians' lack of confidence in politicians in general. Public service announcements on radio and television urged Brazilians not to throw away their votes by casting blank ballots or voting for nonsense candidates. Federal troops were stationed in 15 states and 271 municipalities to keep order. Police arrested some campaign workers for violating a law prohibiting last-minute campaigning within 300 feet of polling stations. The workers were trying to hand out sample ballots with their candidate's name written in. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> voted in his northern home state of <LOCATION> Maranhao </LOCATION>, then returned to the capital of <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, a 58-year-old politician and poet, gained office as the running mate of <PERSON> Tancredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Neves </PERSON>, who was chosen in a military-controlled electoral college vote. <PERSON> Neves </PERSON> died shortly before taking office. The elections are viewed as an important indicator of party popularity as <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> prepares for presidential elections in late 1989, the first such election in 29 years.
