<HEAD>UN Opposes Outside Interference in Central American Peace Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS four grafs on Costa Rica proposal for U.N. observers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The General Assembly on Tuesday adopted a consensus resolution opposing outside interference in the Central American peace process. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> blamed <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for obstructing democracy in the region. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> urges the international community to adopt a realistic and honest appraisal of the disastrous effects of Nicaraguan mismanagement and repression upon the search for peace and democracy in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> alternate representative to the world body. As it did last year, the assembly endorsed by consensus a resolution supporting the peace plan of five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries signed in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Aug. 7, 1987. The five who signed the plan, also known as <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION> II, are <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. But in a change from last year, the resolution said the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> `` appeals to the countries which are outside the region but which have links with it and interests in it to facilitate the implementation of the <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION> II accords and to abstain from any action which may impede such implementation.'' The reference appeared aimed at the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which aides the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, as well as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, both of which arm Salvadoran rebels. The peace plan prohibits foreign aid to rebels. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> told the assembly that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> shares the desire of the Central American peoples for democracy. But she said some `` troubling developments'' and anti-democratic trends in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> were not addressed in the resolution. One year ago, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said, the peace plan represented a mechanism for moving toward democracy. `` Now, we know that the promise is not yet fully realized and that one Central American country -LRB- <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> -RRB- has not lived up to its commitments,'' she said. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said that under the peace plan <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> promised a free press, freedom of assembly and free elections. `` It has delivered on none of these promises,'' she said. Nicaraguan elections have been postponed, the free press is in danger of extinction and political opposition leaders are in jail, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy said. She protested that the resolution calls for international economic cooperation `` despite the absence of any progress by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to grant the freedoms that are basic to building a healthy economy.'' But Nicaraguan Ambassador <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON> told the Assembly that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the Contras was impeding democracy in the region and fulfillment of the peace plan. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was using `` pressure and manipulation of opposition groups ... in an effort to create internal chaos.'' This, he said, had been orchestrated by the former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. He criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration which last week renewed its economic embargo against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. This embargo was declared illegal by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> in June 1986, he said, and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> has demanded its revocation since 1985. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> on Tuesday proposed that neutral observers be stationed along <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s borders with <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrigal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nieto </PERSON> made the suggestion during his address to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. He said stationing <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers would be `` a procedure of verification and control.'' The presence of thousands of Contras in camps in Honduran territory is one of the key obstacles to progress in the peace plan.
