</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet space shuttle Buran orbited the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> twice today and landed eight miles from its launch pad in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, ending with flawless precision its unmanned 3-hour, 25-minute maiden flight. The mission was a major success for the Soviet space program after a series of problems that included the near loss of cosmonauts on a joint Soviet-Afghan mission to the Mir space station in September. The Buran, snowstorm in Russian, touched down on a 2.8-mile concrete runway with a puff of dust from its rear wheels and rolled to a halt as three parachutes opened at its rear. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> has successfully tested its first reusable space craft Buran,'' official <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said, interrupting regular programming two minutes after touchdown.
