<HEAD>Many Illegal Aliens Resort to Phony Documents to Qualify for
Amnesty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Alejandro's Amnesty, b0647</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the promise of legal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residency held before them, thousands and thousands of illegal immigrants are emerging from the shadows under which they harvested <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s fresh fruits and vegetables. In a last, desperate chance to become legal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residents, many of these farmworkers are using fraudulent documents to prove they worked here before, thus qualifying for a legalization program that ends Nov. 30. The Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and organizations working to help the mostly <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> immigrants agree there is massive fraud. But the organizations say the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> has developed a `` paranoia'' over the problem and has coerced applicants into signing `` confessions'' that their documents are phony. Immigration authorities deny the allegation. To qualify for legal residency under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, foreign farmhands must prove they harvested fruits, vegetables or other perishable crops in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for at least 90 days in a one-year period that ended May 1, 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> had estimated that 600,000 farm workers would apply. Instead, the figure topped 1 million by the first week of November, and up to 200,000 more are expected before the filing period ends Nov. 30, according to <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>' Special Agriculture Workers program. Under the initial phase of the legalization program, which ended May 4, temporary residency was granted to more than 1.7 million illegal aliens who proved continuous residency in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since Jan. 1, 1982. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> admits the service was ill-prepared with budget and staff because it underestimated the farmworkers' demand for legalization. To complicate matters, <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON> said, many of the farmhands were unable to obtain the documents they needed. So they turned to labor contractors who hire illegal immigrants, many of whom wrote letters to anyone who asked _ for a fee. `` Every time I call the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, they're screaming fraud, fraud, fraud,'' said <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Brigagliano </PERSON>, an attorney for the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> is going bonkers with this fraud stuff.'' `` The farmworkers are being penalized for fraud when we have created a wonderful black market here,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brigagliano </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, the California-based director of the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Farmworkers' Fund, said she received reports of people paying up to $ 800 for a phony letter, with the average about $ 300 <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> concern over fraud is not paranoia but suspicion that half the undecided cases that have reached processing centers may include phony papers. Nonetheless, he said, early statistics showed a 92 percent approval rate for the first 325,000 applications reaching the centers, where initial decisions are made. Rejections can be appealed to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Those qualifying for legalization under the 90-day prior work provision will receive temporary residency cards, which will be adjusted to permanent status in most cases on Dec. 1, 1990. The immigrants are not required to work in agriculture once admitted. The program also is available to those who can show they worked 90 days in each of three years that ended May 1, 1986, and have resided in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for at least six months for each of those years. They can become permanent residents earlier _ Dec. 1, 1989. The agricultural program was included in the 1986 law at the insistence of growers, especially in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, who argued they needed a pool of legal workers who could be ready to harvest perishable crops on short notice. `` The real test is yet to come,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, senior vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` It will be in the number of workers who remain working in agriculture.'' <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> suggested that those evaluating the program watch how many newly legalized workers show up to pick strawberries in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in January _ the first harvest after the deadline. But for thousands of farmhands seeking a better life, the test begins when they appear at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration office. `` They're being harassed, treated without dignity, told they will go to jail,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> of the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Farmworkers Fund <PERSON> Bodin </PERSON> described most INS personnel as `` cordial, friendly and trying to help'' but acknowledged their job was `` to determine the credibility of the applicant.'' He said farmworkers may find their interviews difficult because they're victims of `` the labor market they've been in.'' `` They were paid in cash, they rode around in a pickup truck, they might not know the names of the farms they worked, only the crew leader's first name,'' he said. `` We try to talk to the applicant and try to get a sense of his credibility. We have gone the last mile. But we can not simply take peoples' word for it. The statute and the regulations require documentary evidence.''
</TEXT>
