<HEAD>Gary Busey Plays Reporter in Miniseries About Fall of Marcos</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto LA1 of Nov. 14</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> named its miniseries about the revolution in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> `` A Dangerous Life,'' it was n't supposed to describe the filming `` When I got to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> they gave me a three-page form to fill out with very personal information to use in negotiations in case I was abducted,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Busey </PERSON>, who stars as a journalist in the three-part, six-hour film airing on Home Box Office this Sunday, Monday and Tuesday. `` A Dangerous Life,'' as seen through the eyes of a reporter, tells of the 1986 `` people's revolution'' that brought down the government of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and brought <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to power as president. During his 5 -LCB- - week stay in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> was accompanied by four bodyguards and three trucks Even so, <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> and the film company were forced to leave the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> on short notice after <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, the former Minister of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, obtained a court order halting production, citing invasion of privacy. Another prominent military officer also filed suit. `` All the judges of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> were out of town,'' said <PERSON> Busey </PERSON>. `` They gave us six hours to get out. We left under armed guard. We went to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> for the interiors then to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to finish the exterior scenes. We finally won the case, but it took months to come to trial.'' <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> stars as <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> on assignment when he witnesses the assassination of opposition leader <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s husband. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' right-hand man, Gen. <PERSON> Fabian </PERSON> <PERSON> Ver </PERSON>, is accused in the murder, but his acquittal spurs <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to challenge <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in the presidential election. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> wins the election amid charges of fraud. Most of the military sides with <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is forced to flee. The miniseries also stars <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilling </PERSON> as <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>'s estranged wife, a fellow journalist; <PERSON> Tessie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> as <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>; <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Rustia </PERSON> as <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>; <PERSON> Laurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillen </PERSON> as <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Joonee </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamboa </PERSON> as <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>. A number of Filipino actors appear in the miniseries, <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> said. `` They were magnificent. They came prepared, they were very disciplined. The focus of the series is a story about their country, which was very important to them. <PERSON> Tessie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON>, who plays <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, used to do a one-woman show on her. <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> loved it. These are actors who are playing people who are still alive who have the ability to get back at them. `` Some members of the cast were pro-Marcos and some were pro-Aquino. We had a lot of tension. My character is a man who gets caught up in the passion of the revolution. I talked to correspondents who covered it. They were very emotional about it. They stayed with the rebel troops. That's where the story was. `` I thought this was going to be easy, but it was like two lifetimes doing this. I learned an awful lot. It was a rewarding experience. I learned a lot about human nature and how democracy works in a Third World country.'' <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> talked about the film on a break from the theatrical feature `` Hider in the House.'' He was in his trailer watching the soap opera `` As the World Turns'' while on location in <LOCATION> Duarte </LOCATION>, about 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` I've been watching this for 25 years,'' he said. `` When I go to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> I visit with these guys. I started watching when I was in college in <LOCATION> Coffeyville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. It's got everything _ sex, blackmail, revenge. It's a great mental catharsis for an actor.'' In `` Hider in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> plays a demented man who takes up residence in the attic of a house being remodeled. The film company was working at the site of an old house that was due to be remodeled. The movie also stars <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McKean </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>.
