<HEAD>Caught in the Middle: The Sandwich Generation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Caught in a vise between the financial needs of children and the care of elderly parents, a generation of Americans is confronted with planning problems that almost defy solution. They are the `` sandwich generation,'' age 45 to 55 years, with college-age children and parents whose incomes are limited. Unlike the very poor, the minorities, the elderly and disadvantaged, this group has little political clout. Its existence barely recognized, it is nevertheless destined to grow because of biological and sociological factors. Among those factors: Parents are living longer, but their income-producing years generally are not being extended. And young marrieds are waiting until the last tick of the biological clock before having children. As a consequence, the sandwich generation's parents become aged and more dependent just as the offspring are preparing for or entering college. Rising tuitions add to the pressure. To deal with the phenomenon, financial planners are seeking creative investment techniques for the sandwich generation, but in almost every instance those techniques require many years to become effective. Moreover, the old and once-trusted method of shifting assets to a controlled trust and automatically getting them back after the demise of the parents does not work any more, thanks to the 1986 Tax Reform Act. In addition, the tax laws make inefficient the simple, direct technique of providing support from the checkbook, because such funding involves after-tax dollars, effectively reducing the benefit to 72 cents on the dollar. The tax law does leave two exceptions, but many members of the sandwich generation may find them inapplicable to them. The exceptions are: _ If you provide more than one-half of a parent's support, and the parent earns less than $ 1,900 a year, you may claim the $ 1,000 dependency exemption on your tax return _ You may claim your parents' medical expenses along with your own as long as you provide one-half of your parents' support And in this case, the $ 1,000 gross income test need not be met. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, an accounting partner in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haskins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sells, believes a member of the sandwich generation should find a way to transfer assets to parents so that the parents instead are taxed. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, who made a special study of the situation, notes that if you transferred titled property to your parents, particularly property with an income, you can effectively move income to their lower tax bracket. One approach along this line would be to set up a trust, put assets in the trust and instruct the trustee to use all income for the parents. This income then becomes taxed to the parents. While you lose total control of the funds, the trust could be so arranged that the assets are distributed as provided in the parents' wills, which means the money could very well revert to you Ms. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> suggests that a second plan would be to create the trust to pay income to the parents for life, with the assets to go to the sandwich generation's children upon the parents' death. This plan might combine support of aging parents at a minimum after-tax cost and provide gifts to children for education. Still, there is no assurance that the money would be available in time to help pay tuition. Another strategy is to have aging parents sell their home and use the funds for support. They would then live in a residence, perhaps a condominium, purchased by their children, who could tap their own home for an equity loan. If all works as intended, these might be among the results: _ The aging parents could shelter up to $ 125,000 of the gain from the sale of their home _ They would have money to live on _ They could pay their children rent _ The sandwich generation members might have tax deductions from their equity loan _ The sandwich generation members might be able to deduct rental property losses _ They also would have an investment that, if it were properly selected, might earn an excellent return None of the solutions is without risk, especially in view of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' inclination to change tax laws. But for those in a very difficult financial squeeze, they at least offer hope that the pain will be reduced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
