<HEAD>Insurance Officials React To Allstate's Plans To Pull Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> insurance officials reacted with surprise to <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to become the third major insurer in two yeras to stop writing new auto insurance policies in the state. `` We had no advance knowledge,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, deputy <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> insurance commissioner, said Monday. `` I guess our overall assessment is we think the company was premature in assessing the effect of the recently passed auto reform bill on the market.'' <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> officials say frustration and the state's regulatory climate prompted the company's decision, which comes amid a wave of anger by insurers nationwide over changing regulatory climates. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> has lost $ 115 million in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> over the past five years, largely as a result of the `` unique regulatory environment'' for auto insurance, said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> division. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> made his comments during a news conference to announce <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>'s decision not to renew its license when it expires June 30. `` We have no intention to return,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. The announcement came about a week after a number of insurers doing business in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> promised to leave that market _ the nation's biggest _ after voters approved a measure providing deep cuts in auto and other insurance rates. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> will continue selling new policies and follow through on all its <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> policies until they expire, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. Last week, a bill was signed into law that will reduce 1989 insurance premiums in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> by 16 percent, or $ 400 million, by cracking down on fraud and abuse in the system, reducing required coverages and limiting the number of auto cases that end up in court. The legislation came after industry court challenges and rate decisions increased rates by nearly one third since 1986 to among the highest in the country. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> saw some encouraging improvements for consumers in the bill. But <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said it did little or nothing to restore free markets to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> state law requires all companies wishing to sell any form of insurance in the state to participate in an open `` high-risk'' auto insurance pool. State law also forbids open competition for automobile insurance. Instead, the state insurance commissioner annually calculates a single statewide rate for each category of compulsory and optional insurance. Only <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has a similar system. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, has been doing business in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> since 1951. The company has 6.6 percent of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> auto insurance market and 5.2 percent of the state's homeowners insurance market <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> accounts for some $ 199 million of <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>'s premiums annually, or about 2 percent of the company's business in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> has 573 full - and part-time employees at several locations in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> will `` make every effort to try to relocate qualified employees'' and predicted there would be few or no layoffs. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, voters last week approved Proposition 103, which mandates that property and casualty insurers roll their rates back to a level 20 percent below those in effect on Nov. 8, 1987. In a addition, drivers with good records would get an additional 20 percent off. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has delayed the start of the law while it considers its constitutionality. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> was confident the insurers would prevail in court. He also said <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> had no intention to pull out of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which he described as quite different from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in that it allows `` open competition.'' More than 100 companies sell auto insurance in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, but 90 percent of the coverage is written by the top 25 insurers. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> ranked fourth in statewide market share. <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>'s departure was preceded in the past two years by <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fireman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> and two smaller companies. All cited millions of dollars in losses in the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> auto market for their decisions. To continue writing other forms of insurance in the state, <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> recently won state regulatory and legislative approval to set up a spinoff company to assume its auto insurance business. Fireman's Fund, meanwhile, agreed to pay a $ 45 million settlement to the state as compensation to the high-risk drivers' pool so it could abandon the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> market. Since reaching that settlement last year, the company has proposed buying a subsidiary firm with <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> licenses so Fireman's Fund could re-enter the state and sell other forms of insurance.
