<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> faced a major image problem from a minor part of its insurance business, but the company's handling of controversy over its drought insurance should keep its name relatively unclouded, analysts say. `` They really exhibited the type of concern about the quality of their business and their reputation,'' said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> took a major step toward putting the controversy behind it last week when it announced a $ 48 million settlement to a class-action suit representing 8,000 farmers in 10 midwestern states. Farmers had sued when applications for insurance over this summer's drought were denied. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> still must approve the settlement. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>, based in <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, was prepared to offer $ 40 million in insurance for below average rainfall. But brokers sold more than $ 300 million in coverage, enraging the farmers who were denied coverage and prompting at least seven state insurance departments to launch proceedings against the company. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> took steps to repair the damage, including granting $ 11 million in goodwill payments, setting up a crisis center to answer questions and taking out newspaper advertisements, all in advance of last week's settlement. `` I think they as a company want to get this behind them'' and `` out of the press,'' said <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION>