<HEAD>Federal Judge Blocks West Point-Pepperell's Defense Against Farley
Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officers of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point-Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, denied the use of their `` poison pill'' takeover defense, will have to come up with another way to battle a $ 1.4 billion buyout bid from <ORGANIZATION> Farley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> granted a temporary injunction Monday blocking the Georgia-based textile maker from using the pill against <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>'s $ 48-a-share takeover attempt The judge also refused to grant <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> two preliminary injunctions it sought against <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Downs </PERSON> said the company plans to appeal <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON>'s ruling and declined further comment. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> now must fight more aggressively to overcome the bid, said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronston </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The ruling `` weakens their case, and it becomes incumbent upon <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> managers to come up with their own offer,'' she said. That offer to stockholders could include a leveraged buyout of the company, a restructuring that would include the sale of <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> assets or a `` white knight'' that would make a friendly counter offer for ownership of the company, Ms. <PERSON> Bronston </PERSON> said. The West Point-based diversified manufacturer of consumer soft goods including Arrow shirts and <ORGANIZATION> Martex </ORGANIZATION> towels sought to protect itself against a possible takeover by Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Farley </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 2.87 million shares, or 9.8 percent, of <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> stock. <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, a maker of clothing, including Fruit of the Loom underwear, and precision metal products, announced its attempt to buy <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> May 23. <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>'s offer is based on 16.73 million shares being tendered, and other conditions, and expires at midnight EST, Nov. 21. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> stock closed Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> at $ 42 per share, down 87 -LCB- cents. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s board created the pill in October 1987 to protect itself against a possible hostile takeover. The pill allowed stockholders not involved in a takeover attempt to purchase additional shares, which would sharply increase the cost of a buyout. In response to suits by both corporations against each other and other defendants over the plan, <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> voided the rights agreement. `` The court finds no authority in either the state law or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>'s Articles of Incorporation which authorize the rights plan,'' <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> wrote. He said the plan discriminated among shareholders because some were given rights not allowed others in a takeover attempt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, chairman of the company seeking to take over <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>, said, `` We are pleased by the court's ruling and believe that it will facilitate the successful completion of our offer.'' `` In light of the court's decision, we believe that the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> board should recommend the acceptance of our offer, which is a full and fair one.'' <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOC