<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury has awarded $ 3.8 million to three former <ORGANIZATION> Quasar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> employees, all over 50, who were fired and whose duties were transferred to younger men, their attorneys say. A federal jury Monday awarded $ 1.9 million _ between $ 508,000 and $ 713,000 to each man _ but the total amount was being doubled to $ 3.8 million because the jury found the discrimination was willful, the attorneys said. Quasar, a sales subsidiary of Japanese-owned <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Paramus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, dismissed <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortino </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> and <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON> during a 1986 company restructuring that affected approximately 200 workers in <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. Attorney <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bashwiner </PERSON>, who represented Quasar, declined to comment on the verdict. `` There were several tip-offs that discrimination might be a part of the picture,'' said plaintiff attorney <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>. `` The company continued to hire new people. The vast majority of them were very young, under 40. `` They told our clients that their jobs were being eliminated, but they reassigned those functions to younger people,'' he said. <PERSON> Fortino </PERSON>, 58, had been assistant general manager of the advertising and sales promotion department at Quasar's <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> facility since March 1979. He was awarded $ 508,857, or $ 1.01 million when doubled. <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, 53, was a nine-year employee and manager of sales administration at the site. He receives $ 728,223, or $ 1.45 million when doubled. <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON>, 54, had worked for Quasar and its former owner, <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, since 1957. When he was forced to leave, he was national manager of physical distribution. He was awarded $ 713,908 or $ 1.42 million. The jury rejected a claim made by a fourth former worker, <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mustachio </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>.
