h an investment bank was in effect helping take over a company. BNS would then be disbanded, and <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> would become fully responsible for debt incurred in the <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> takeover. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> owns 46.1 percent of BNS, and a National Westminster subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NatWest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, owns 4.9 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> owns 49 percent. The transfers are part of a refinancing in which a consortium led by <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> will lend <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> $ 2.3 billion. About $ 1.3 billion of that will refinance debt from the takeover and $ 570 million will substitute for money <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> planned to raise by selling high-yield junk bonds, the British company said in a letter to shareholders. By not issuing the bonds, <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> expects to save $ 25 million in interest expense. The remaining $ 400 million will be temporary financing to be repaid by future sales from <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' chemical operations.
