<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mostly Lower In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting disappointment about the size of corn sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and a weakening technical picture. The corn market registered little excitement about the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s purchase of 300,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced the sale late Monday after the corn market already had closed higher on rumors the Soviets had bought as much as 2 million metric tons of corn, analysts said. Wheat prices were narrowly mixed this morning while soybeans were under pressure due to weakening chart signals, which prompted one independent trader to unload a large amount of futures contracts. `` The beans are acting pretty well as far I'm concened, especially with someone pounding on them like that,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON>, a grain market specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. In early trading, wheat was 1 \ cents lower to 2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.19 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1 -RCB- cents lower with December at $ 2.70 \ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 \ cents lower with December at $ 2.12 -LCB- a bushel; and soybeans were unchanged to 3 -LCB- cents lower with November at $ 7.55 -LCB- Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .33 cent to .70 cent higher with December at 72.95 cents a