<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 19-20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>High Plains Cotton Farmers Expecting Second Big Crop in A Row</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Having plowed the financial harvest of 1987 into this year's crop, cotton farmers of the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> are expecting to reap bountiful results again this fall. With the harvest in full swing, crop observers are forecasting a total yield of about 2.7 million bales from 3 million acres for the 25-county area that stretches from <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION> in the Panhandle of the state, south to <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. That's slightly below last year's bumper crop of 2.7 million bales from 2.7 million acres, which marked the second-highest per-acre yield on record behind 1965 when slightly more than one bale an acre was harvested. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> leads all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> states in cotton production, and the <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> area alone produces more than any state except <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The 1987 crop eased financial burdens on many farmers, allowing them to pay off loans and buy new equipment. Unlike years past, during this growing season they had some money to spend on better fertilizer, more irrigation and pest control. `` People were in a better position to invest a little more in this crop,'' said cotton agronomist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Supak </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've gone through some pretty tough ones. People are still working largely on borrowed money, but it was a little easier to finance this crop because of the better production last year.'' The weather also played a big part in what should be back-to-back crop successes. Warm and dry conditions in October improved yield prospects by about 10 percent over earlier forecasts, say crop observers. As a result, the cotton bolls, or seed pods, matured before a freeze could kill the plants. Area growers could have been tending an even better crop had more rainfall soaked fields during the summer. `` This could have been an exceptional crop, perhaps a record crop, had we caught a rain in August,'' <PERSON> Supak </PERSON> said. `` The dryland cotton went through a pretty severe drought stress. That will put a cap on production.'' Crops in most areas were spared from severe hail damage, which all but devastated the 1986 crop, but drought conditions will cut into the harvest in some areas of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>, an extension agent in one <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION>, estimated that farmers in his area would bring in only about 8,000 bales over 55,000 acres, compared with 22,000 bales last year. Scant rainfall and boll weevil infestation in the area, where dryland farming predominates, doomed crops early on. `` We did n't have any rain through July, August or September,'' said <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>. `` The drier it got, the worse the bugs got us, and before we knew it we did n't have any cotton.'' Still, state agriculture officials project that <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' cotton crop will be the fourth-largest in 10 years, down about 7 percent from 1987. While cotton experts say the quality of this year's <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> cotton has been good so far, market prices have edged lower. `` It appears that the demand for cotton is somewhat weaker now than it was at this time last year, especially the export demand,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Ethridge </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s agricultural economics department. `` I also see that there is some weakness in the domestic demand for cotton, and that is certainly affecting the market price.'' <PERSON> Ethridge </PERSON> attributed the weakness in demand to a sluggish economy. But the <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> economy should pick up as a result of consecutive bountiful harvests, said L.J. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brownfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` Since agriculture is the base of the economy in <LOCATION> Brownfield </LOCATION> ... it just has a tremendous impact on our local economy and the financial institutions,'' he said. The influx of deposits from last year's crop boosted <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> to a record $ 94 million in assets. `` We expect that when we get this crop in, we'll reach the $ 100 million mark,'' he said. Despite the hopeful outlook, weather-related misfortunes could still befall the cotton before it's out of the field later this month, said <PERSON> Supak </PERSON>. `` What would tend to hurt us would be weather systems that would come in here with ice and snow and moisture,'' he said. `` Cotton is very vulnerable at this stage to weathering and will lose its color if exposed to moisture.''
</TEXT>
