<HEAD>Poly-Tech Presents a Bag as Degradable as the Trash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the makers of Ruffies are accurate in their view of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, making gains in the garbage bag business is a matter of appealing to the nation's conscience. <ORGANIZATION> Poly-Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, is launching a line of degradable plastic trash bags with hopes that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households will pay a little extra for Ruffies knowing they have the potential to turn to dust. `` We've gotten just a tremendous response,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <PERSON> Poly-Tech </PERSON>, a company founded in 1958 by flamboyant philanthropist <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, who sold out in 1969. `` It's going to be interesting to see if people will go out and buy those products.'' It's not the first time degradable garbage bags have been marketed, but <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON> says <PERSON> Ruffies </PERSON> is the first nationally advertised brand to make the move. `` On their part it's smart marketing,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rolfes </PERSON>, a securities analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. `` I think people like to do the environmentally right thing.'' By adding photo-sensitive material to the plastic compound, the bags break down when they are exposed to ultraviolet light from the sun. Once the chain reaction begins, the bags eventually are reduced to a fine powder, the company says. The bags will completely degrade in about three months in direct sunlight, the company says. But there's a catch. <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON> said bags must be exposed to the sun a minimum of about seven days for the breakdown process to begin _ give or take a few days depending on seasons and the bag's distance from the equator Given the dark nature of landfills, `` most bags wo n't degrade with the way they are normally used,'' <PERSON> Rolfes </PERSON> said. Still, degradable bags are helpful in the fight against litter and even the darkest landfill ca n't stop the degrading process of a bag once it starts, <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON> said. The technology will add about a dime to the retail cost of a package of 30 tall kitchen container-sized bags, which vary in price from $ 1.99 to $ 2.69 depending on where they are sold. `` Hopefully, there's some profit there, but it's not a wildly profitable thing,'' <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON> said. Ruffies, with about 400 employees in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Battleboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, controls about 8 percent of the total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer trash bag market while its two other national competitors _ Glad and Hefty _ each has about a 30 percent share, <PERSON> Doernbach </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Poly-Tech </ORGANIZATION> posted $ 71.8 million in revenues in 1987 but earned just $ 472,000. <PERSON> Rolfes </PERSON> said the degradable bags could give Poly-Tech a small sales edge in some locations, but not enough to make a `` night-and-day difference'' because the product could easily be duplicated by competitors if it skyrockets. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>, product manager for Glad trash bags in <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, said he's neither surprised nor worried about the change in <LOCATION> Ruffies </LOCATION>. `` This is not a hot button with consumers,'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> said. `` -LRB- Poly-Tech -RRB- is responding to special interests.'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes Hefty bags, said it's a waste of time and resources to make garbage bags degradable. `` The degrading process takes far, far too long to create extra space in landfills,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. `` The money is much better spent on real solutions to the problems.'' Although plastics only account for an estimated 7.2 percent of the country's solid waste as measured by weight, many experts believe plastics pose a much greater problem than the figures reveal because they are so light. About 9.6 million tons of plastic were discarded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1984 and the volume is expected to increase 9.8 percent to 15.5 tons by 1990. Recycling, garbage incineration and reducing the stream of solid waste are environmental causes more worthy of corporate concern, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. `` It's a matter of taking care of the volume that we generate and reducing that volume,'' he said. Still, Hefty will be keeping an eye on Ruffies sales to see what consumers want. `` <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s position has been, if the market demands that the bags be made biodegradable we'll do it,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
