<FIRST>a f BC-Brazil-GoldFever Adv21   11-15 1152</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Gold Fever, Adv 21,1188</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Nov. 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Amazon Gold Fever Attracts Almost 1 Million to Jungles</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTO VELHO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Behind his ramshackle wooden counter <PERSON> Luiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> Costa sells anything from toilet paper and cigarettes to cooking oil and rice, literally for the price of gold. His prices are calculated in grams of the yellow metal _ one-tenth of a gram -LRB- worth about $ 2 -RRB- for a dozen eggs or a half a gram for 2 pounds of coffee. Costa's customers are part of an estimated 1 million prospectors who have invaded <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s vast <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest to tap its rich gold deposits. Fortunes are made. But the gold rush also is creating widespread violence, smuggling, tax evasion, health problems, environmental pollution and even the disturbance of primitive Indians. The gold dust, which Costa carefully weighs on his scale, comes from the bed of the <LOCATION> Madeira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that flows past <LOCATION> Teotonio </LOCATION>, a small prospectors camp 25 miles from <LOCATION> Porto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Velho </LOCATION>, capital of the western jungle state of <LOCATION> Rondonia </LOCATION>, about 2,000 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. `` This is my way of digging for gold,'' said <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION>, a 58-year-old, pot-bellied, toothless man who claimed he was too old to put up with the rough-and-tumble life led by most gold diggers. According to <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Altino </PERSON> <PERSON> Machado </PERSON>, a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prospectors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, there are close to 3,000 gold-digging sites spread out over the 2 million square miles of the so-called Legal <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>, comprised of the states of <LOCATION> Amapa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Para </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Roraima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maranhao </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Goias </LOCATION>, Acre, <LOCATION> Rondonia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mato </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosso </PERSON> and Amazonas. Since the late 1970s, `` close to 600,000 newcomers have swelled the ranks of the 400,000 professional prospectors who have been working in the region for years. And if you include spinoff services such as food, equipment, transportation and prostitution, the number of people living off the gold rush jumps to 7 million,'' <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> said. Most prospectors were poor peasants fleeing <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s drought-ridden Northeast But over the past few years `` businessmen, doctors and lawyers have also become gold diggers. They make more in six months than in five years behind their desks,'' <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> said. He said a prospector extracts on the average at least 50 grams of gold -LRB- worth about $ 1,000 -RRB- a month. Most work for well-established entrepreneurs who take 70 percent of the production in exchange for equipment, transportation, medicine and food. `` Very few get rich,'' <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> said. But fortunes are made in the jungle. About 5,000 prospectors have earned at least $ 1 million, and some 200 are worth more than $ 5 million, he said. Most of the gold from the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> never finds its way into the national economy. Buyers who purchase the gold directly from the prospectors hoard it or acquire dollars as a hedge against inflation, or smuggle it out of the country to evade income and mineral extraction taxes. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Maron </PERSON>, an official of the Mines and <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mineral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` lack of funds and manpower make it almost impossible to police the vast expanse of land on which the gold digging sites are located.'' In an interview, <PERSON> Maron </PERSON> said that of the estimated 100 tons of gold produced in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in 1987 `` only 35 tons were registered with the government.'' For 1988, he estimated a `` real production of 110 tons versus a registered production of no more than 55 tons.'' Ministry figures show that between 1977 and 1986 almost $ 23 billion of gold was `` detoured from the economy.'' In terms of real production, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> ranks sixth among the world's largest gold producers coming after <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> <PERSON> Maron </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has known reserves of 1,000 tons of gold. He said geological studies have not been made to pinpoint gold reserves in the Amazons `` but all told I would estimate <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has a potential of producing about 30,000 tons of gold.'' `` A lot of gold is found inside Indian territory. This has led to several conflicts, especially with the <ORGANIZATION> Yanomami </ORGANIZATION> tribe in the northern state of <LOCATION> Roraima </LOCATION>, near the frontier with <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Maron </PERSON> said. Police and army troops occasionally evict prospectors from <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> territory, `` but they keep coming back,'' he said. <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> admitted prospectors work near <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> territory, `` but never invade it. It is the Indians who enter prospectors' camps and dig for gold and they are always welcomed.'' <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> gold comes from huge open-pit mines or is blasted from the earth with high pressure water hoses, pumped from riverbeds or simply panned by solitary prospectors. The most serious environmental hazard posed is the use of mercury, a metallic chemical element used to join gold dust particles. The mercury is burned off the gold, emitting a highly toxic gas that enters the atmosphere and can be inhaled by the prospector. The toxins can cause nervous disorders and genetic deformations in offspring. <PERSON> Maron </PERSON> said 180 tons of mercury enter the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>'s ecosystem every year `` affecting the region's flora and fauna and poisoning the rivers.'' Along a 370-mile stretch of the <LOCATION> Madeira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, some 5,000 dredges daily suck up huge amounts of gravel, which yield more than 4 tons of gold a year. Near the Teotonio prospectors camp, <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliveira </PERSON> employs 16 men on his two dredges, which operate 24 hours a day. Seventy-three feet below, hoses acting like giant vacuum cleaners pump up about 6 tons of gravel per hour. On hundreds of small barges, competing with dredges for space, divers plunge into the dark, muddy waters, hand-carrying smaller versions of the suction hoses. <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lins </PERSON>, 23, dives twice a day. Air, pumped through a tube by an engine on the barge, allows him to remain underwater for two hours at a time. <PERSON> Lins </PERSON>' profession is a dangerous one. He runs the risk of bursting his lungs by getting his air tube tangled with those of other divers or with the dredges' hoses. Divers are also known to cut their rivals' air supplies. `` Scores die this way each year,'' <PERSON> Lins </PERSON> said as he prepared to dive. But it's not only divers who die for gold. Each day at least four people are shot dead in <LOCATION> Teotonio </LOCATION> `` mainly because they did n't obey our unwritten code of ethics,'' said <PERSON> Oliveira </PERSON>. `` Here it's live and let live and work and let work. Anyone who does n't follow this rule dies.'' <PERSON> Machado </PERSON>, <PERSON> Oliveira </PERSON> and other prospectors interviewed denied reports that drug traffickers from neighboring <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> cross frontiers to exchange cocaine for gold. `` But we have information of traffickers buying gold with dollars as part of their money-laundering process,'' <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> said. More than 1,000 gold fever-stricken prospectors enter the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> each year hoping to strike it rich, and according to <PERSON> Machado </PERSON>, `` Very few will leave the jungle, because once you come down with the fever you never want to recover.''
</TEXT>
