<HEAD>Bipartisan Commission Chairman Says Gasoline Tax Hike Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> told oil industry executives Tuesday that an increase in the gasoline tax could become a reality under the new administration. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a prominent <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat, said a new tax on gasoline had been discussed as one possible way to help reduce the federal government's huge budget deficit. `` A great many experts feel ... that if indeed additional revenue is needed ... that a gas tax or a broad-based energy tax is something the government should look at very strongly,'' <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> told some 1,500 participants at the closing session of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting. However, <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> declined to say whether he had or would recommend a new gasoline tax to the commission, a bipartisan body formed to make recommendations on reducing the budget deficit. During the three-day meeting, industry leaders have spoken out against new taxes, arguing that the oil industry is the most heavily taxed in the nation. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> has called the retail gasoline tax the `` single most regressive form of taxation,'' one that would tax the low income most heavily and have a harmful regional impact <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON>, who also is chairman of the trade group, said Tuesday that while President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had promised not tol resources, it is more environmentally acceptable than other fossil fuels _ and particularly so in addressing such concerns as ozone, acid rain and the greenhouse effect,'' <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> said.
