<HEAD>Major Carriers Put Off End to Short-term Advance Fare Discounts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to clarify and UPDATE with Continental also
extending; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, ``Other carriers ...;
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines have put off for another week the elimination of a popular category of discount air fares, the so-called `` junk fare'' used by major business travelers. The cuts, which represented an industrywide restructuring of discount fare programs, had been scheduled to take place today. But officials of several carriers said today they had decided to extend the deadline to Nov. 22. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which initiated last Friday the move to eliminate the fares, has extended them for the same period, according to travel agents. Continental spokesmen were unavailable for comment today. `` Other carriers made that move and we simply matched it,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, a spokesman for Dallas-based American. <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said he could not provide an explanation for the postponement. However, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today one reason for the change was that some carriers, including <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, had not yet put the new fares into effect. `` I think all the airlines are watching each other,'' said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornacker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, said the airline had joined in the delay because of confusion among passengers and travel agents over elimination of the discount fare. `` I think passengers became confused and travel agents and we wanted to give time for them to sort these issues out,'' <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said. The fare changes involve the discontinuation of most three - to seven-day advance-purchase fares Besides having the relatively short advance-purchase requirements the so-called junk fares often did not require a traveler to stay at the destination on a Saturday night. They also were between 10 percent to 35 percent below full coach fare.
</TEXT>
