<FIRST>r f BC-SteelImports     11-15 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Steel Imports,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Import Needs Will Change Little</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will need just about as much imported steel next year as this year even if an economic recession reduces overall steel consumption, a leading steel importer said. The requirement for foreign steel will be a central issue in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, as debate heightens over the extent to which President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should renew steel import quotas due to expire next Sept. 30. Domestic producers can not sustain production much above 80 percent of rated capacity, and exports are expected to grow, said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamesch </PERSON>, president of the importer <ORGANIZATION> TradeARBED </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and past president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imported </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>. For this year, domestic shipments are expected to reach 83 million tons, imports 21 million tons and exports 2 million tons, leaving total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption of 102 million tons, he said Monday night in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> during an address to members of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>. `` Let's assume steel consumption drops five million tons to 97 million tons next year. If, as widely forecast, exports rise by two million tons, we would still need 20 million tons of imported steel in this market. And for specific products and regions, dependence on imported steel is much greater,'' <PERSON> Lamesch </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lamesch </PERSON> said domestic producers can be expected, among other things, to begin filing unfair trade cases as early as spring, as they lobby for an extension of the trade restraint agreements. `` Domestic producers prefer a situation in which the sum of their own capacity plus imports does not surpass a level that will threaten future price stability,'' the importer said. `` In practice that translates into an effort, first to keep closed domestic capacity from being reopened and, second, to extend and expand restraint agreements.''
</TEXT>
