<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   11-15 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 16,0660</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Nov. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Small Businesses More Optimistic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Small businesses are feeling better about the economic outlook these days, with an increasing number thinking about adding more jobs, building new plants and maintaining relatively high inventory levels. But do n't expect to see too much in the way of salary increases over the next few months, according to the latest quarterly survey by a leading trade group. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> _ whose 500,000 member firms employ about half the country's non-farm work force _ reports that its small-business optimism index rose to 102.9 in October from 100.5 in July. The seasonally adjusted index, which assumes conditions that existed in 1978 equal 100, reached a high of 108.7 in January 1984 and a low of 81.1 in April 1980. Earlier this year it had been slippping. `` Firms had become decidedly less optimistic about future economic growth during the year,'' explained <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON>, dean of <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school and originator of the survey. `` But the declines of early 1988 were reversed in October ... returning to levels that prevailed in 1986 and early 1987.'' The data compiled in the survey of 2,084 small responding businesses includes predictions on expected business conditions, the climate for expansion, earnings, job openings and hiring plans and plans for capital outlays. <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON> said the overall sentiment of responding firms could be summed up this way: `` There is still no sign that there is substantial weakness in the economy or that a recession is likely to start anytime before mid-1989. `` Strong earnings are supporting strong plans to hire and spend on inventories and capital projects.'' Among details of the report: _ Eighteen percent of the firms plan to increase total employment in the next three months, while 11 percent plan reductions The percentage of firms with job openings set a record for the current expansion, rising to 25 percent and surpassing the previous high of 23 percent last January. `` The employment rate should continue to fall under such pressure,'' the report said. _ Twenty-nine percent reported raising prices in the third quarter, unchanged from the previous period, while 8 percent reduced prices, down two percentage points from July Plans to lift prices fell one percentage point from July levels, to 25 percent of all firms. `` Although not large, there is a clear upward drift in the percent of firms planning to raise prices. -LRB- But -RRB- ... non-food inflation should fall off somewhat in the fourth quarter,'' the report said. _ Planned capital outlays rose to an all-time seasonally adjusted high of 35 percent Fifty-five percent reported outlays in the last six months, although the spending rate is still nine percentage points below the high level set in 1979. _ Plans to add to inventories were unchanged from July levels, but remained strong in comparison to the past four years Seventeen percent planned to add to inventories, while 17 percent planned to reduce. `` Accumulations have been heavy among retail and wholesale firms, perhaps in anticipation of the Christmas selling season,'' the report said. _ The percentage of firms borrowing on a regular basis rose to 38 percent from a record-low 35 percent of all firms `` Apparently profits and cash flow are sufficient to meet he capital needs of most small firms.'' _ Twenty-six percent reported increases in employee wages in the third quarter of 1988, up one percentage point from the previous period Plans to increase wages rose three percentage points to 21 percent of firms. `` With job openings at expansion-high levels, there is still little evidence that compensation is responsiding in any substantive way to labor market tightness,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Nov. 16</NOTE>
