<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Down 2 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> reported that its profit declined 2 percent in its second quarter as its 1987 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caledonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> continued to reduce earnings. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s largest airline said Tuesday that its net profit in the three months ended Sept. 30 fell to 91 million pounds, or around $ 165 million, from 93 million pounds, or $ 168 million, a year earlier. Per-share earnings slipped to 12.6 pence, or 23 cents, from 12.9 pence, or 23 cents at prevailing exchange rates. The decline occurred despite a 12 percent rise in second-quarter revenue, to 1.19 billion pounds, or $ 2.2 billion, from 1.06 billion pounds, or $ 1.9 billion. The latest quarterly results for the airline were in line with most analysts' forecasts. In the first six months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>' profit fell 5 percent to 144 million pounds, or $ 261 million, from 151 million pounds, or $ 273 million Per-share earnings declined to 20 pence, or 36 cents, from 20.9 pence, or 38 cents. Half-year revenue rose 13 percent to 2.21 billion pounds, or $ 4 billion, from 1.96 billion pounds, or $ 3.5 billion. Results for the former British Caledonian operations, acquired by <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> last year for 253 million pounds, or $ 458 million, were included in the figures for the current fiscal year but not in those of the previous year. <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> Chairman Lord <PERSON> King </PERSON> said second-quarter results from most market segments were satisfactory but that there was a disappointing performance from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and British operations. `` The winter months are our most vulnerable period,'' he said. `` However, present -LRB- passenger -RRB- traffic levels remain high for this time of year and our forward bookings are ahead of last year.''
