<HEAD>Siemens Offers To Inspect, Fix Circuit Breaker Boxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The maker of I-T-E circuit breaker boxes is offering to inspect and repair, if necessary, breaker boxes which could overheat and malfunction, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday. According to the manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Alpharetta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, some of the breaker boxes were made with incorrect components. The I-T-E circuit breaker boxes, or `` load centers,'' can be identified by the five-digit code marked on top of the wiring diagram label inside the door. Those in question are: H2586-H3186, made Aug. 25-31, 1986. J0186-J30-86, made Sept. 1-30, 1986. K0186-K2486, made Oct. 1-24, 1986. If the wiring diagram has a sticker labeled `` inspected lugs,'' it already has been checked and corrected if necessary, <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> reported. Anyone finding boxes with the codes in question but without the inspected sticker should contact <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> at 1-800-334-2982 or the <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, 1-800-638-2772.
