<HEAD>Polls Finds Budget Gap Biggest Concern of Small Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of the nation's small-business owners believe the federal budget deficit is the No. 1 issue facing President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and they favor spending cuts to reduce the shortfall, a poll said Tuesday. The 21,000 entreprenuers responding to <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anderson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s third annual Small Business Survey also expressed general optimism about the economic outlook despite the lingering budgetary problems Two-thirds of those polled said the deficit was the most pressing issue of the day. Forty-five percent listed tax rates, 26 percent domestic programs, 25 percent foreign policy and 15 percent defense spending. The respondents were asked to pick the two most important political issues facing the incoming administration. Spending cuts were picked by 55 percent of those surveyed as the best solution to the deficit problem, while 44 percent favored both spending cuts and increased taxes. `` Emerging and owner-managed businesses appear to see taxes as both a concern and a reality,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Halloran </PERSON>, an <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> partner. `` To reduce our deficit, most small businesses prefer a reduction in spending by cutting defense spending, welfare and foreign aid.'' As far as the economy was concerned, 60 percent of the respondents predicted they would record at least a 5 percent gain in sales in the upcoming year, with 35 percent foresaw an increase of more than 10 percent. Three-fourths estimated profits would stay the same or increase over last year. `` In past studies, the executives' predictions have been right on target because they are aware of their competitive environment and the pressures facing small business, and are committed to setting and reaching optimistic goals,'' <PERSON> O'Halloran </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, is one of the world's largest accounting and tax consultants.
