<FIRST>r f AM-API     11-15 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-API,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Facing Serious Energy Problems, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Falling energy prices and rising profits at many oil companies are concealing more serious industrywide problems that a national energy policy must address, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` The truth is that the state of the nation's energy health today is perceived as ` good' only because enough inexpensive foreign oil is available,'' the industry's main trade group said in a report. `` Our condition could turn to ` poor' or ` critical' if that supply were disrupted ...'' The report, `` Energy Security White Paper: <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Decisions and Global Trends,'' was issued during the group's annual meeting. The survival of domestic exploration and production is in question as lower crude prices discourage investment in new oil development, the report said. Dependence on foreign oil, primarily from the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, has increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vulnerability to the dangers of a supply disruption and price volatility, it said. Despite recent huge quarterly profits by major oil companies, the gains came in `` downstream'' sectors such as refining and chemical manufacturing, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON>, president of the trade group. But the favorable earnings were offset at least partly by losses in `` upstream'' _ production and exploration operations _ stemming from low crude prices. The paper calls for a national energy policy to ensure an adequate and secure supply of oil at reasonable prices while reducing vulnerability to a future oil crisis. The report does not specifically call for tax incentives to help offset the crude prices, but contends correct `` government decisions'' could increase domestic oil supply by 2 million barrels a day by the end of the 1990s. Only 921 oil rigs are working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, compared with about 1,000 a year ago and 4,000 in 1981, the group noted. Those rigs are producing approximately 8 million barrels of oil a day and output is falling 3 percent a year while demand is rising about 2 percent annually, the report said. Consequently, foreign imports have soared to 43 percent from 31 percent just three years ago and some economists predict that in five years the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may be importing half of its oil. The report said dependence on foreign supplies, primarily from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vulnerability to a supply disruption. With demand increasing rapidly, the current glut of oil on world markets could dry up in the 1990s, the report said. `` Then any number of unpredictable developments around the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> could directly, swiftly and critically affect oil supply,'' the paper said. In addition, another steep plunge in oil prices, like that which occurred in 1986, threatens the survival of smaller oil companies, damages the economies of oil states dependent on the industry for revenue and `` hurts the country's long-term energy security,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
