<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar edged downward Tuesday in uncertain trading in advance of Wednesday's report on the nation's merchandise trade deficit for the month of September Gold prices rose. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold bullion was bid at $ 423.00 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $ 422.85 late Monday. Forecasts of the trade deficit ranged widely from $ 9 billion to $ 11 billion. Traders said any number above the range would be likely to drive the dollar lower, while a figure below the range probably would spark a rally. `` Eight or 12 -LRB- billion dollars -RRB- is clearly going to move the markets,'' said <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyski </PERSON>, a portfolio manager of <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Trade deficits and the markets' reaction to them are notoriously difficult to predict. Currency dealers said sentiment toward the dollar is predominantly bearish, and any rally caused by a good trade number might be quickly swamped by a wave of selling. The trade deficit in August was $ 12.2 billion. Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was slightly helped Tuesday by the government's report of a rise of 0.9 percent in retail sales in October, the biggest increase in seven months. Strong economic growth attracts investors to dollar-denominated securities. The market shrugged off a 0.4 percent advance in industrial production in October, which fell within expectations, traders said. In contrast to other recent sessions, there were no reports of intervention by central banks to support the dollar against other currencies. The dollar had rallied on Monday on the strength of central-bank purchases and reassuring statements from officials of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 123.25 Japanese yen from 123.00 yen Monday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar traded higher at 123.40 yen. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 123.23 yen from 123.75 yen Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound fell to $ 1.8060 from $ 1.8090 late Monday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound rose to $ 1.8083 from $ 1.8074. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday, included: 1.7433 West German marks, down from 1.7465; 1.4626 Swiss francs, down from 1.4665; 1.2337 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2313; 5.9535 French francs, down from 5.9635; and 1,297.00 Italian lire, down from 1,300.25. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday, included: 1.7465 West German marks, up from 1.7452; 1.4630 Swiss francs, down from 1.4645; 5.9660 French francs, up from 5.9615; 1.9685 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9735; 1,300.50 Italian lire, down from 1,303.50, and 1.2344 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2297. Gold prices moved higher, but traders said there was n't enough interest in the metal to sustain a big rise. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 424.07 a troy ounce, up from $ 422.51 an ounce late Monday. Gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 423.75 a troy ounce, up from $ 420.95 late Monday. The late Zurich price was $ 423.00 an ounce, up from $ 420.00. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery rose to $ 424.40 a troy ounce from $ 423.90 at Monday's close. Silver bullion rose in 