<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge Despite Continuing Strike in Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices plummeted Tuesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as edgy speculators ignored bullish supply-and-demand factors and sold heavily on fears that the market had topped. On other markets, precious metals were mixed; grains and soybeans were lower; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; energy futures retreated; and stock-index futures advanced. The miners' strike in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, the world's sixth-largest copper producer, entered its fifth week with no hint of a settlement but most futures traders sold the market anyway. Copper settled 2.7 cents to 6.1 cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 1.299 a pound and the spot November contract at $ 1.369 a pound, about 17 cents below the record high of $ 1.538 reached Nov. 2. `` The market is caught in the throes of bearish sentiment,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON>, metals market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` It's sort of like a snowball going down a hill,'' <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON> said. `` It tends to gain momentum to the downside.'' The sell-off was sparked by weakening technical signals, the chart patterns followed by many speculators, he said. As more people sold, prices kept falling to levels that triggered further selling. But <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON> noted that last year's extraordinary copper rally, which saw prices hit $ 1.46 a pound on New Year's Eve, included a 20-cent correction, so the price slide of the past two weeks was not unprecedented. `` This does n't indicate the market is incapable of resuming its upside move,'' he said. `` The fundamental situation to me still portends upward prices.'' In addition to the Peruvian strike, bullish fundamentals include tight supplies and strong demand for copper, which is heavily used for construction and by almost every industry. Gold futures rose slightly but silver prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled 40 cents to 60 cents higher with December at $ 425.60 a troy ounce; silver was 5 cents to 5.2 cents lower with December at $ 6.393 a troy ounce. Soybean futures prices settled at a 3 -LCB- - month low on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on a late round of speculative selling Corn also finished sharply lower while wheat futures were mixed. Prices were weak all session amid bearish chart signals and disappointment over the relatively slow pace of grain exports. Even the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement late Monday of a 300,000-metric-ton corn sale to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> did not rally the corn market, which was expecting a Soviet corn purchase of up to 2 million metric tons. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON>, manager of CBOT floor operations for <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said most of the selling was done by speculators while the outnumbered buyers were largely commercial traders. `` There's just not enough cash business right now to support these price levels,'' <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON> said. `` And if you ca n't go up, you've got to go down. Wheat settled 7 cents lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.13 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 5 -LCB- cents lower with December at $ 2.66 a bushel; oats were 3 -RCB- cents lower to -LCB- cent higher with December at $ 2.10 a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 15 -LCB- cents lower with November at $ 7.43 -LCB- a bushel. Cattle futures settled sharply higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, buoyed by improving cash markets and strong buying by commercial players, analysts said. Pork futures enjoyed some spillover support from the adjacent cattle pits but gains were limited by expectations of lower cash prices on Wednesday and concerns about the rapid buildup of pork bellies in cold storage. Live cattle settled .70 cent to 1.25 cents higher with December at 73.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to 1.30 cents higher with November at 82.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .27 cent lower to .38 cent higher with December at 41.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .40 cent higher with February at 44.87 cents a pound. Oil futures prices drifted lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in dull, directionless trading, reversing the gains of the previous session. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 32 cents to 37 cents lower with December at $ 13.90 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to .69 cent lower with December at 44.40 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .55 cent to 1.20 cents lower with December at 46.96 cents a gallon. Stock-index futures posted modest gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for December delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 settled .65 point higher at 269.50.
