<HEAD>Appeals Court Refuses 2-1, to Remove Judge in Drexel Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 3-4 with SEC comment, picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Drexel has...SUBS last three grafs to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A divided federal appeals court on Tuesday refused to oust <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> from presiding over the civil insider trading case against investment giant <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In a 2-to-1 decision, the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> declined to intervene and remove <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> over an alleged conflict of interest. The Wall Street firm did not immediately say whether it will appeal further. But the decision was welcomed by officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which brought the massive civil-fraud case against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> more than two months ago. `` Naturally we're pleased,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goelzer </PERSON>, general counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` We did n't feel that Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> was required to recuse -LRB- disqualify -RRB- himself and the court agreed with us.'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has claimed that it is playing a key role in financing the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Palais </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Houston-based retailing company in which <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s wife <LOCATION> Moselle </LOCATION> is a major stockholder. Although she has no direct relationship with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> stands to gain about $ 35 million in the transaction. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and other defendants, including <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s high-yield bond financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, have contended that their connection to the judge's wife creates an appearance of partiality by <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> toward them. They have requested another judge that would make the case free of any possible taint. In sometimes heated court sessions, <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, an 82-year-old jurist with a pro-government reputation, balked at stepping aside, calling the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> move an `` illusionary diversion.'' Other lawyers familiar with the case have called the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> move a tactical strategy to get another judge because of fear by defense attorneys that <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> would rule harshly against the firm. `` We conclude that an objective observer knowing and understanding all the facts and circumstances could not reasonably question Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s impartiality,'' wrote Circuit Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardamone </PERSON>, with Judge <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> concurring. But Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lumbard </PERSON> disagreed in a sharply worded dissenting opinion, saying: `` It is clear to me that a reasonable person knowing these ultimate conceded facts would reasonably question Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s ability to supervise such litigation impartially. `` Such a reasonable person's next question would be ` Why has n't the judge stepped aside? Moreover, Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s expressed resentment to the suggestion of recusal and his castigation of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and its counsel has confirmed these doubts. He can not act impartially in these cases,'' <PERSON> Lumbard </PERSON> wrote. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said `` we naturally are disappointed with today's decision in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. We have not yet had an opportunity to review it, and we will be doing so in the next few days.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filed a 184-page civil fraud complaint against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and three other employees Sept. 7, accusing them of trading on inside information, cheating clients, manipulating stock, keeping phony books and other violations. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> also claimed <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> used the organization of convicted takeover speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> as a front for its alleged illegal activities. The defendants have denied any wrongdoing.
