<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car and light truck sales by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers rose 14.9 percent in early November compared with results a year ago that were depressed by the absence of buyer incentives. The seven manufacturers assembling cars and light trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said Tuesday they sold 295,497 vehicles during the Nov. 1-10 period this year, compared with 228,665 vehicles during the same time last year. That amounted to a 14.9 percent increase in the daily sales rate. There were nine selling days during the period this year and eight last year. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers have sold 10,190,150 vehicles in 1988, a 7.6 percent increase over the 9,437,194 sold during the Jan. 1-Nov. 10 period last year There have been 266 selling days so far this year, one more than at the same time last year. `` That's very olid,'' analyst <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> said of the sales figures. `` Our outlook calls for continued moderate steady growth without any ripples.'' <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON>, an auto analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said, `` The'89 model year is starting off very, very well.'' Part of the reason for the increase in year-to-year sales was a lack of incentives in early November last year. The super-low financing and big cash-back offers of last summer ended with the 1987 model year on Sept. 30, 1987. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA