<HEAD>ICC Overturns Arbitrator's Ruling In New England Rail Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday overturned a federal arbitrator's ruling that would have reinstated union pay rates and work rules that were slashed by <ORGANIZATION> Guilford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> last year in a sweeping cost-cutting reorganization. The <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION>, on a 3-1 vote, ordered that union and company negotiators return to the arbitrator's mediation table to try to work out new pay rates and work rules for the freight line, the largest privately-owned railroad in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Last year, <PERSON> Guilford </PERSON> reorganized its subsidaries, <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION>, putting them under <ORGANIZATION> Springfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Terminal </ORGANIZATION>, a tiny rail line with much lower wage scales. <LOCATION> Guilford </LOCATION> officials argued that the move was necessary to cut costs and keep the company competitive. In June, arbitrator <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasher </PERSON> ruled that workers transferred to <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Terminal </LOCATION> must be the wages they received under their <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Central contracts and be subject to the work rules under those pacts. But <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON>, ruling Tuesday on an appeal from the company, said the arbitrator's decision on pay rates and work rules failed to give <LOCATION> Guilford </LOCATION> officials `` management flexibility.'' She voted with the majority to send the issue back to the arbitrator and negotiators for mediation, although she noted that `` we have never seen anything to lead us to believe that -LRB- the two sides -RRB- can or will come up with an agreement.'' `` Our objective is we want to see this railroad operate. We want to see management be fair to labor. We want to see labor be fair to management,'' she said. `` It's tempting to impose a solution here today, but we believe you understand your business better than anybody else.'' Commissioner <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, voting with <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON> and Commissioner <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andre </PERSON>, said she feared that forcing <PERSON> Guilford </PERSON> to comply with the old union wage scales and work rules would cripple the company and its ability to compete. <ORGANIZATION> Guilford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Billerica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. company owned by <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON>, a reclusive heir to the <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> banking family of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, reorganized last year, saying it could not compete under the union wage and rule restrictions. In a statement released following the commission meeting, the company said it would `` wok within the process prescribed by the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> in the hope that it will pave the way for the railroad to meet the competitive challenges of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> marketplace while at the same time meeting the requirements of the railroad's employees.'' Commissioner <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamboley </PERSON>, the lone dissenter, said it was inappropriate to `` dissect'' portions of the arbitrator's decision. `` You ca n't break out bits and pieces of it,'' he said, adding that the commission was venturing into an area beyond its expertise. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyden </PERSON>, international vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said he was disappointed with the commission's ruling on pay rates and work rules, but applauded the panel's votes upholding other sections of the arbitrator's decision The commission ruled 4-0 to affirm <PERSON> Kasher </PERSON>'s decision to provide <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Central workers not rehired by <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Terminal </LOCATION> with severance pay and benefits in accordance with the old contracts. And the commission agreed that workers hired by <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Terminal </LOCATION> must receive the difference between their new salaries and their old, higher wages for up to six years. But the workers would be subject to the new work rules that <LOCATION> Guilford </LOCATION> officials say would make the company more efficient. The commission also voted unanimously to require <PERSON> Guilford </PERSON> to honor the seniority employees built up at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION>.
