<HEAD>Continental Plan Could Boost Most MaxSaver Fares</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf pvs, Some examples...to CORRECT that fares are
one-way sted round trip. Picks up 19th graf, _Between Newark,
N.J....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just days after initiating an industry move to drop discounts aimed at business travelers, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> announced a restructured `` MaxSaver'' program Tuesday that is expected to boost most remaining cut-rate fares. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> said MaxSaver fares _ which are used by most vacation travelers _ would be based on the length of a flight under the new formula. Competition on individual routes, not mileage, had determined the fares in the past. It was not immediately clear whether other big carriers would follow <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s move, but the airline has been the pacesetter on fares in recent years. The airline planned to notify travel agents about the new fares Tuesday night and Wednesday, spokesman <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. He said the new MaxSaver fares would take effect next Wednesday. `` You will see some MaxSavers going up and some MaxSavers going down,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` We are returning air fares to a more rational level.'' He said fares for longer flights generally would be raised while those for shorter hauls would mostly be reduced. Some travel agents told about the changes said they appeared to have the effect of raising roughly two-thirds of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s MaxSaver fares and cutting the remaining third or so `` They're going to raise it to the level that it should have been in the first place,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, the owner of JB's <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. MaxSaver tickets must be purchased seven to 14 days in advance and require an overnight stay. Air fare structures have become geographically `` out of whack'' as a result of airlines frequently matching each other's fare increases in recent months, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The changes come amid plans by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and other big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines to eliminate another category of discount air fares _ the `` junk fares'' available four to seven days before a flight and used mainly by business travelers. In a move initiated by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and followed by several major carriers, the junk fares were slated to be eliminated on Tuesday. But the airlines decided to extend the deadline by a week because of confusion over the change. Only about 10 percent to 20 percent of all airline passengers use the last-minute junk fares, according to some analysts' estimates. The popular MaxSaver fares, by contrast, are used by most vacation travelers. More than 90 percent of air travelers use some form of discount fare, be it last-minute or advance purchase, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an industry trade group based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The discounts generally are n't available for flights during holidays like Thanksgiving and Christmas. Some examples of changes in <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s one-way MaxSaver fares are: _ Between <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>: current off-peak fare, $ 129; current peak fare, $ 159; new off-peak, $ 139; new peak, unchanged _ Between <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>: current off-peak, $ 149; current peak, $ 169; new off-peak and peak, both unchanged _ Between <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>: current off-peak, $ 174, current peak, $ 204; new off-peak, $ 159; new peak, $ 179 _ Between <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>: current off-peak, $ 159; current peak, $ 184; new off-peak, $ 179; new peak, $ 199 _ Between <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>: current off-peak, $ 114; current peak, $ 144; new off-peak, $ 129; new peak, $ 149
