<HEAD>Union Members Vote To Accept New Contract; Mickey Mouse Won't
Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a union coalition representing 9,200 workers at <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to accept a new three-year contract, ending a strike threat against the giant tourist attraction. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Totzke </PERSON>, president of the six-union <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, reported union members voted 1,059-677 to approve the agreement, which provided for immediate pay raises of 35 cents to 50 cents. Asked about two previous rejections of similar offers and repeated calls by some union members for a strike, <PERSON> Totzke </PERSON> said: `` I think they finally took a realistic look at the offer. I can say it now it was a fair offer. We got all we could get.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> vice president for labor relations, said, `` I'm obviously very happy about it We felt that we had a good contract.'' Rejection by two-thirds of the voters would have authorized labor leaders to call a strike. Among the workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> are ride operators, sandwich makers, bus drivers, stockroom workers, hotel housekeepers and clerks, animal handlers, monorail pilots and the people who portray <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Duck </PERSON>, Goofy and other characters. The company has said it was prepared for normal operations in the event of a strike. Disney officials planned to fill park operating jobs from among the 13,000-plus non-union employees, and from among management, workers who chose not to observe a strike call and any people hired after a strike call. The balloting was the second within four days. An election last Friday was nullified by union bosses who discovered some workers voted more than once. Angry employees rejected two earlier contract proposals, contending they did not offer enough money for pay raises. The new contract provides pay raises of 50 cents an hour to workers now at top scale, who earn from $ 6.80 to $ 9.70 an hour, and raises of 35 cents an hour for workers below top scale, who now make $ 4.85 to $ 9.20 an hour. In April 1990, workers at top scale would get pay hikes of 45 cents an hour, while those below top scale would receive 30 cents an hour. Workers rejected an earlier package offering wage increases of 5 percent in the first year and 4 percent in each of the contract's final two years, plus other benefits Dissatisfaction by many union members dates back to 1985, when the unions agreed to a two-year wage freeze and took one-time bonuses instead. Two weeks later, the company announced record revenue and profit for its 1985 fiscal year, union members said. The Service Trades Council is composed of the <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Restaurant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>.
