<SECOND>BC-United Pilots,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes One Contract Provision Pilots Said Hindered Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has struck down a provision of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' contract with union machinists, ruling the language was intended to hinder the pilots union's attempt to buy the carrier, union and company officials said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> sued in April to block two provisions in <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s contract with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> on the grounds. The pilots union claimed the provisions were restrictive covenants aimed at blocking its more than $ 4 billion proposal to buy the airline, said <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> on Saturday rejected one provision, which would have prohibited the pilots' union from participating in an employee ownership plan unless the machinists and other unions agreed to the terms, <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for corporate communications, said late Tuesday the airline would have no comment on the ruling. United spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> confirmed <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>'s rejection of the provision, but said Tuesday he did not know the details of the lawsuit or of the judge's decision. <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> said that under the stricken provision, any stock ownership option tendered to the pilots would have to be offered to the other unions and subjected to possible arbitration. `` We'd be in the position of trying to buy a company and not knowing what the price was going to be until after arbitration,'' <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> said. Local 1487 of the Machinists, which negotiated the contract with <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement confirming <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>'s rejection of the provision, but made no further comment. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>, president of the local, was in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on Tuesday and would not be available for comment until next week, said a union officer who declined to be identified. <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> let stand the second provision challenged in the <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> lawsuit. That provision would give the Machinists a choice of reneging on their existing contract or extending it for three years in the event of any takeover. In April 1987, the machinists refused to join <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> in its buyout attempt, citing what union officials called philosophical and technical problems with the pilots' proposal. Despite that refusal, <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said last December they considered the possibility of a sympathy strike against <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> if the machinists and the airline failed to agree on a contract. The machinists' pact, containing the two provisions challenged by <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>, was reached Nov. 15, 1987, hours before expiration of a 30-day `` cooling-off'' period. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>, which has made three offers to acquire the airline, has enlisted the aid of a syndicate of banks and the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The pilots' first proposal for a $ 4.5 billion employee takeover of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> was made in April 1987 and rejected by its parent <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that same month as inadequate. Two months later, in June 1987, <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> came back with a recapitalization plan, under which ownership of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> would have been transferred to employees and stockholders. The company also rejected that proposal.
