dollar trading, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar moved higher against the Japanese yen in Wednesday morning trading, while share prices rose to another record high on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar opened at 123.58 yen, up from Tuesday's close of 123.25 yen, and by late morning was changing hands at 123.50 yen. Exchange dealers said activity was slow as investors waited for the release of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report on the nation's September trade deficit, scheduled for later Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` But in general, the market sentiment toward the dollar is bearish,'' said an exchange dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's main price index, rose 99.21 points from Tuesday's record close to finish the morning session at 28,928.62, a record for the early session On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, dealers said the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index briefly topped the 29,000-point mark for the first time, but moved back slightly due to profit-taking. `` Share prices appear to be as bullish as they can be,'' said a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Financial shares were down today but other shares, such as construction, are leading the market.'' The dealer said it was a good sign that different types of issues were variously leading the market. `` As long as this sort of cycle continues, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> will continue to grow for some time,'' he said.
