<FIRST>u f BC-CalInsurance     11-15 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cal Insurance,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rate Intitative Reaction Hit Business Harder than Consumers, Study
Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the insurance companies that quit selling and renewing policies after last week's voter approval of a rate-cutting initiative have returned to the market, according to an industry survey released Tuesday. But far fewer companies are offering homeowners' and business liability policies, according to the survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> and Brokers of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The survey, which gauged the market as of Monday, suggested that fears of mass insurer defections from the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> market after last week's passage of Proposition 103 _ a ballot initiative that would deeply cut insurance rates _ were exaggerated. Numerous companies suspended policy sales and renewals after the initiative passed last Tuesday. But many have returned to the market since the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, acting on an industry lawsuit, put the measure on hold pending a trial. As of Monday, the brokers' group found, companies making up 81 percent of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> market were selling new auto insurance policies. Renewals were being offered by companies representing 94 percent of the market. For reasons the group has yet to determine, the figures were far lower for homeowners and business policies. Insurers accounting for 75 percent of the market for homeowners' policies were selling new policies, while renewals were available from companies making up 83 percent of the market New commercial insurance policies were available from companies holding just 54 percent of that market, and renewals were available in 66 percent of the market. The figures are based on direct communication with 75 insurance carriers that hold more than 90 percent of the market, and were valid as of Monday, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Annotti </PERSON>, spokesman for the agents' group While the high court's stay has returned stability to the market, the long-term health of the industry _ and the availability of insurance to consumers _ depends on the outcome of the lawsuit, <PERSON> Annotti </PERSON> said. He repeated frequent industry warnings that most insurers would incur unacceptable losses if Proposition 103 were upheld. The measure, backed by consumer crusader <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, was approved by voters who rejected four other competing initiatives proposed by industry or trial lawyers' groups. Proposition 103's principal effect would be to roll rates for nearly all types of insurance back to November 1987 levels, and then impose an additional 20 percent cut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>